<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan Urged to Settle Differences Through Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The president of the U.N.
Security Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said here Wednesday
that his Council hopes both India and Pakistan to solve their
problems through bilateral consultations.
</P>
<P>
In answering a Xinhua question, the president said, "Members of
the Council encourages both India and Pakistan to settle their
problems through bilateral consultations."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council took note of a statement issued by
(U.N.) the Secretary-General," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks after the 15-nation Security
Council pondered over a Tuesday incident that a Pakistani plane
was downed by Indian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday expressed regret at
the loss of life resulting from India's downing of a Pakistani
plane and called on both countries to "exercise maximum
restraint."
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general regrets the loss of life following the
downing of a Pakistani aircraft by the Indian Air Force," Annan
said in a statement issued through his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The statement came in response to the shooting down by an
Indian combat aircraft of a Pakistani maritime patrol aircraft
that India said had strayed into its airspace.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan said the unarmed plane was shot down well within its
territory and that all 16 aboard had been killed. It reserved the
right "to make an appropriate response in self-defence."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman said Annan was "increasingly concerned at
the repeated incidents between India and Pakistan and urges that
the differences between them be resolved by peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
"He calls on both countries to exercise maximum restraint," the
satement said, "The secretary-general looks forward to an early
resumption of the bilateral dialogue between the two countries in
the spirit of the Lahore Declaration."
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani and Indian prime ministers promised in Lahore in
February this year to intensify efforts to resolve all issues
between them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
