<HEADLINE> Security Council Backs OAU Efforts to End Horn of  Africa War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
said Wednesday that the 15-nation body will continue to support
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in its efforts to end the
conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Council, Martin Andjaba of Namibia, said, the members of the
Council "expressed their full satisfaction and support for the
continuing efforts of the Organization of African Unity."
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council reaffirmed their willingness to
consider appropriate support to implement a peace agreement
between the two parties," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement after the Council was briefed
on Wednesday morning by Mohamed Sahnoun, the U.N. special envoy in
Africa, on progress towards negotiated settlement of the conflict
between the two African countries.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council commended the OAU, including the OAU
Chairman and President of Algeria Abdelaziz Bouteflika and
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim" for their efforts to put an
end to the conflict on the Horn of Africa, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The war broke out in May 1998 when Eritrean forces occupied
disputed territory along the two nations' shared 1,000-kilometer
border. The border has not been officially demarcated since
Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
