<HEADLINE> Arab League Denounces Israeli Action Against Al-Aqsa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Wednesday
strongly denounced Israel's recent seal of an opening of Al-Aqsa
Mosque in Jerusalem, Islam's third holiest site.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based league termed the action an "attack" aimed at
further frustrating the Muslims and breaching the holiness of the
Islamic sanctity.
</P>
<P>
Such practice contradicts Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
pledges to advance the Middle East peace process, the 22-nation
pan-Arab forum said.
</P>
<P>
Israel wants to impose its presence and hegemony in Jerusalem,
denying the rights of Arab Muslims and Christians, the Arab League
said.
</P>
<P>
It urged the world community to press Israel to guarantee
Muslim's freedom of worship in Al-Aqsa Mosque and the human rights
of the Palestinian people, keep the demography or legal status of
the city intact, implement international resolutions, and refrain
from unilateral actions before the final status talks with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1947 U.N. resolution, Jerusalem should be under the
control of the world organization. But Israel occupied the whole
city in the 1948 and the 1967 Mideast war and has declared the
city as its "eternal and undivided" capital.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want the traditional Arab East Jerusalem as
the capital of their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel will discuss the fate of Jerusalem
in the final status talks that should have started by May 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
