<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks with Barak over Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton has
talked by phone with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak over the
prospect for the Middle East peace process, the White House said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
David Leavy, spokesman for White House National Security
Council, said the two leader spoke for about 25 minutes on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"They talked about the peace process generally, reviewed the
situation on the ground, talked about all tracks, including the
Palestinian track and Syria and Lebanon," Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
Leavy also said Clinton and Barak discussed ways to make
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's trip to the Middle East a
success.
</P>
<P>
Albright, at Barak's request, has postponed her trip to the
region to give the Israeli leader more time to work out his
problems with the Palestinians over the timing for carrying out
last year's Wye River land-for-security agreement.
</P>
<P>
Before going, Albright intends to meet in Washington with the
senior Palestinian negotiator Aseb Erekat and with Yasser
Arafat's deputy, Mahmoud Abbas, widely known also as Abu Mazen.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said both Clinton's
talks with Barak and Albright's planned meeting with Palestinian
officials here are "designed to see how we can be as helpful as
possible, both in insuring the implementation of the Wye River
agreement as well as assisting the parties in pursuing a permanent
peace accord."
</P>
<P>
"Those two objectives are what Albright will be working on,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright is due in Jerusalem on September 2 and will hold talks
there with Israeli officials. Then she will be in Gaza to meet
with Palestinians and in Damascus to hold talks with Syrian
officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
