<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Defendant Hearing Held, Inquiry Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The court hearing for the
arrested German businessman Helmut Hofer was held Wednesday in
the presence of his lawyer at Tehran's public court.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for Tehran Justice Department Saeed Noubari said
the inquiry into Hofer's charges was adjourned until the next
court hearing and the judge will announce a date for further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was arrested in September 1997 for illicit sexual
relations with an Iranian woman and was sentenced to death
in January 1998. Iranian laws prohibit affairs between a
non-Muslim man and a Muslim woman.
</P>
<P>
However, Hofer argued that he had converted to Islam before
having an affair with the Iranian woman. The death sentence
was then rejected by Iran's Supreme Court, which ordered a
retrial.
</P>
<P>
He was released from jail on bail in April but was again put
behind bars in August. The reason for his re-arrest, according to
judicial officials, was his "links with certain foreign elements
and the possibility of his fleeing from the country."
</P>
<P>
Nobari had been quoted by the official Islamic Republic News
Agency as saying "Hofer's charges are of the kind that according
to the law, must be held behind closed doors."
</P>
<P>
Hofer's lawyer Malek Houshang Qahhari had explained that
according to law, any court where talk may be made of unethical
issues, should be held behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
He had said he was not aware of any possible fresh charges
against his client. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
