<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Prevalence Reduced by Half in Uganda: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Painstaking efforts have
successfully curbed the spreading of AIDS and HIV in Uganda with
HIV infection rate reduced by half in the past few years, an
official with Uganda AIDS Commission told Xinhua Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Anne Nakaweesi, coordinator with the AIDS organization,
said:"Although this is a big achievement, but the rate is still
unacceptably high." The infection rate still stands at 12 percent
in the east African country which once had the highest rate in the
world of some 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
"At Nsambya hospital sentinel site, the HIV infection rate has
declined from 29.5 percent in 1992 to 13.4 percent in 1998. These
declines have been most marked among the 15-19 year olds. Among
the above age group, the infection rate fell from 32.2 percent in
1991 to 10.3 percent in 1997," the official noted.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator attributed this progress to the government's
sensitization work, effective anti-HIV/AIDS measures including
setting up of counselling centers and safe sex.
</P>
<P>
Since the first case of AIDS was reported in the country in
1982, more than 1.5 million people have died of the epidemic. The
HIV infection rate was over 30 percent in early 1990s. Now Uganda
is the only African country which has reduced its HIV prevalence
rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
