<HEADLINE> Mozambique Against Sending Troops to Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Foreign Minister
Leonardo Simao said here Wednesday that the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) summit in Maputo next Wednesday will
not decide to provide human and material resources to help the
Angolan government fight the UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
It is inappropriate to send troops in any form, the minister
was quoted by the Mozambique News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Simao said that his government will take stand on the
Angolan crisis after the summit has worked out a framework.
</P>
<P>
"The SADC summit will make evaluation (of the situation in
Angola)," he said, adding that only after the evaluation, decision
could be made on what to do.
</P>
<P>
The minister pledged that Mozambique will always contribute to
the peace cause of the world.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the closure of the Christian broadcasting station
Eclesia and the arrests of the director and three reporters by the
Angolan government, Simao said that it was understandable because
Angola is still in war.
</P>
<P>
The authorities has the right to take measures to prevent
anything harmful to the national security, especially when the
situation is tense, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende
told a press conference Tuesday that many possibilities including
military intervention in Angola exist, but it is up to the
regional leaders to decide what to do at the coming summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
