<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Trade Deficit Soars in First 7 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli trade deficit rose to
4.3 billion U.S. dollars in the first seven months of 1999, up
29.6 percent over the same period last year, the Central Bureau of
Statistic reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, import rose by 7
percent, reaching 17.1 billion dollars, the report said. Export
only saw a slight 1 percent growth, amounting to 12.8 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
About half the deficit rise derived from the import of
civilian aircraft and another 36 percent from the import of raw
diamonds, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Export of diamonds rose in January-July period by 13 percent,
or 380 million dollars while the import of raw diamonds increased
by 32 percent, or 750 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit increase came after a continuous decline in
1997 and 1998, with a 25 percent decrease each year, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
As its economy becomes more and more independent, Israel has
narrowed its gap between import and export in recent years, but
the worldwide financial chaos last year has hampered its exports.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that recent figures showed that the trade
deficit has stabilized at a high level. The monthly increase in
export since April comes to only 0.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
