<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polio Vaccination Campaign Launched in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda has launched a
countrywide campaign of vaccination against polio for all children
aged five and below, sources from the Ministry of Health told
Rwanda News Agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Ezechias Rwabuhihi underscored that the massive
polio eradication campaign is aimed at kicking out polio once for
all by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The population has been mobilized and sensitized for a long
time, and therefore they are aware of its necessity and are
seriously responding to the government's initiative," the minister
declared.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the same ministry said that during the last
immunization campaign held in March this year, the northwestern
prefectures of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri had the lowest turn-outs
which was 77 percent whereas countrywide results were 92 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The northwestern prefectures had the poorest turn-outs due to
the insecurity which was rocking the region. However, we expect
the highest outcome this time in the range of 100 percent," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Most of the sub-Saharan countries have got the best performance
in polio eradication campaign because they followed up the
required procedures unlike Rwanda, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that immunization campaign will continue not only with
the eradication of polio, but also on tuberculosis, measles,
whooping cough as well as other related diseases.
</P>
<P>
The next immunization campaign against polio and vitamin A
provision to curb night-blindness will continue in mid next
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
