<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak FM Dismisses Indian Claims of Warning Before Downing Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Wednesday dismissed the Indian claims that they gave a
warning to the Pakistan navy plane before shooting it down
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Talking with the media here Wednesday, Aziz said that
Pakistan's air control station did not hear anything about the
warning claimed by India.
</P>
<P>
"If the Indians had given a warning it should have been heard
by the Pakistani air control," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know what kind of response did they (Indians) expect,
because that warning should have been heard by our air control,
both civilian and air force, and they did not hear anything about
that," Aziz said, referring to India's claims that they had warned
at 11:15 a.m. Indian time and shot down at 11:17.
</P>
<P>
Aziz rejected the Indian claims that the wreckage of the
unarmed Pakistan Navy plane is lying 10 kilometers on the Indian
side.
</P>
<P>
"Our people have taken foreign correspondents there who have
seen the wreckage two kilometers inside our territory," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
"Within three hours after the plane was shot and before our
people found the wreckage the Indians came in helicopters and took
away some pieces. Otherwise, how could it land 10 kilometers
away," he argued.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister termed the Indian action "unprovoked and
cowardly act" because this was an unarmed plane. "They knew it was
a propeller plane," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
