<HEADLINE> 3 Former Zimbabwean Freedom Fighters Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- At least three ex-combatants were
arrested at the National Heroes Acre in Harare Wednesday, the
Zimbabwe Liberation War Veterans Association said.
</P>
<P>
National chairman of the association Chenjerai Hunzvi told the
Zimbabwe News agency that the arrests included Harare province
vice-chairman of the association Mike Moyo who attended the
celebrations of the Heroes Day at the Acre.
</P>
<P>
Moyo last month led about 1,000 ex-combatants to besiege both
the State House and the headquarters of the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union, demanding to meet their patron President
Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The arrests came as a surprise as the three had not threatened
anyone, Hunzvi said, adding that it was the government that had
tried to provoke the war veterans by making the arrests.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no way the former freedom fighters would have
engaged in violence as they respected the fallen liberation war
heroes.
</P>
<P>
He added that war veterans were not enemies of the state but
were patriotic and wanted to see the people united.
</P>
<P>
"We are calling for the release of the three forthwith. We
have been living under harassment from the state for too long,"
said a visibly angry Hunzvi.
</P>
<P>
The government had deployed a number of riot police officers at
the shrine, the venue for the Heroes Day celebrations, in
anticipation of a demonstration from the ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the riot police were also deployed at the ruling
party headquarters and around the city center preparing to clash
with the former fighters who intended to hold a demonstration for
more pension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
