<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Cheer Eclipse in French Historical City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOYON, France, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people
cheered the total eclipse which occurred at around 12:25 local
time (10:25 GMT) in this small historical city in northern France
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite heavy clouds and a little rain, the fantastic scenery
of the sun being eaten away by the moon could still be seen from
time to time from an observation ground at the outskirt of Noyon,
the birthplace of the great Christian religion reformer Jean
Calvin (1509-1564).
</P>
<P>
Against the background of the grandiose Notre-Dame Catheral
with its unique early Gothic architecture, where Emperor
Charlemagne was crowned by the Church 1000 years ago, people from
many countries of Europe camped on the ground waiting to see the
crescant sun since early morning.
</P>
<P>
Situated at the medium line of the ``total eclipse belt'' in
northern France, Noyon was chosen as the observation site by the
Astronomic Society of France for the last total eclipse of the 2nd
millennium.
</P>
<P>
At around 12:20, the sky became dark as if a big storm was
about to come. Five minutes later, it was night.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from 14 European member countries of the European
Space Agency, plus many amateur astrologists and professional
photographers, attended the ceremony in Noyon.
</P>
<P>
The whole town of Noyon was in an atmosphere of festival, with
music melodies on the sun being played by the organizers. Children
asked scientists naive but amusing questions about the sun and
outer space at a broadcasting station.
</P>
<P>
Many visitors also had a chance to discover this beautiful
French city with a great northern heritage, which remains
relatively unvisited by foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
