<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most UAE Residents Stay at Home in Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Heeding warnings of health
departments, most residents of the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
stayed at home Wednesday afternoon to avoid hurting eyes by
looking at the sun directly in the eclipse.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city of Abu Dhabi, pedestrians and vehicles
reduced sharply in streets. The usually noisy construction sites
became quiet.
</P>
<P>
In response to a government announcement, all federal
ministries, departments, companies and other private firms ended
their work at 10:00 a.m. (0900 GMT) in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The government said the decision was taken for the safety of
citizens and residents against the adverse effects of the partial
eclipse, which took place from around 3:00 p.m. (1400 GMT) to 5:25
p.m. (1625 GMT). A maximum of 87 percent of the sun could be
blocked by the moon during this period.
</P>
<P>
"You must stay indoors to avoid the potential damage to your
eyes and skin caused by the strong sun rays during the eclipse,"
said the keeper of a grocery store. He said the store would remain
open though business could be affected for a few hours.
</P>
<P>
Although most of the people were following the government's
instruction to stay indoors and watch the millennium's last solar
eclipse on TV, some residents did enjoy observing the phenomenon
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
Near the famous fountain attraction on the Abu Dahbi Corniche,
where people usually take walks in the evening, hundreds of
astronomy fans were holding a huge party.
</P>
<P>
Many of the fans, from different nationalities, were
clustering around two telescopes provided by the Amateur Astronomy
Section of the Emirates Heritage Club. The telescopes could
reflect the image of the eclipse onto a white board.
</P>
<P>
Others were watching the partly-covered sun with special
glasses or negatives, ignoring the government's warning that the
so-called solar glasses bought from the market could not protect
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
"I came here out of a kind of curiosity," said a young UAE
national, resting in the shade of a big tree and wiping off the
sweat on his face. He added that this was the first time he
watched an eclipse.
</P>
<P>
"The newspapers have been talking about this rare phenomenon
for quite a few days and now everybody knows that the sun will
have some problems today," said a middle-aged Indian. "Through
watching this phenomenon, one can learn some astronomical
knowledge," he added.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the astronomy section said choosing the
observing site meant to help common people know more about this
astronomical phenomenon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Foils 3 Indian Attempts to Steal Wreckage of Downed Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has foiled three
attempts by India to take away the wreckage of the Pakistan Navy
plane shot down by Indian jet fighter planes inside Pakistani
territory Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have repulsed three such attempts by India," Vice Chief of
Naval Staff Admiral Aziz Mirza said here Wednesday at a press
briefing which was also attended by Information Minister Mushahid
Hussain and Foreign Office spokesman Tariq Altaf.
</P>
<P>
Mirza said Pakistan has deployed naval marines, SSG and
Pakistan armymen at the site where the wreckage of downed plane
was lying.
</P>
<P>
Following the shooting down of Pakistan Navy's Atlantic plane
Tuesday well inside the Pakistani side at around 11:20 a.m.
Tuesday, the Indian choppers sneaked into Pakistani airspace upto
14:55 p.m. when Pakistan traced out the wreckage of downed
aircraft, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
"We have found the traces of the landing of an Indian chopper
at the site which may have managed to take away some items of the
wreckage," Mirza said. "This incident took place before we spotted
the wreckage of the plane at 14:55 hours."
</P>
<P>
There were two further incidents of this kind later in the day,
said Mirza.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about reports that Pakistan had fired
missile on Indian choppers which tried to land at the site of
wreckage, he said, "It is quite likely because the wreckage is
lying on our side of the boundary and we have stated in clear
terms that we reserve the right to give appropriate response to
(any intrusion or aggression)."
</P>
<P>
To another question, he said Pakistan's contention that the
Atlantic plane was on a normal training mission was substantiated
by the fact that it was not given cover of the fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
"Had this plane been on reconnaissance mission, it must have
been given a fighter planes cover," he said. "A plane flying on a
routine mission in peace time is never provided with such a
cover."
</P>
<P>
Mirza also said Pakistan Air Force (PAF) planes also scrambled
into the air after the Karachi radar system detected two Indian
fighter aircraft in aggressive posturing in the vicinity of the
downed plane.
</P>
<P>
"But the Indian jets had shot down the Pakistani Navy plane
before PAF aircraft reached the area," said Mirza.
</P>
<P>
"PAF planes were 100 nautical miles away from the Atlantic
plane when the incident took place," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said a warning should be issued to a plane in case of an
aggressive posturing before taking extreme step of shooting it
down.
</P>
<P>
"Our plane had not committed any mistake at all for it had not
crossed into Indian territory and it is obvious from the fact that
its wreckage is lying well inside Pakistani territory," he said.
"Hence the shooting down of the plane was totally unwarranted and
reprehensible."
</P>
<P>
Mirza also rebuffed the claims of Indian Defense Minister
George Fernendes that Indian fighters shot down the Pakistan Navy
plane after it ignored the warning.
</P>
<P>
"That warning would have been recorded with Karachi and Badin
radar systems but there was no such warning from the Indian side,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
