<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-11 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Countries Urged to Help Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 11 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday called on
developed countries to help developing countries to face the
challenges in the process of economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
Yongtu Long, Chinese vice-minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation made the call here at the ministerial meeting
of the Asian member states of the Group 77 (G77).
</P>
<P>
He said that economic globalization is an inevitable result of
the high-speed growth of world economy, science and technology and
thus every nation has to face it.
</P>
<P>
The globalization presents precious opportunities as well as
harsh challenges, he said, adding countries which conducted
policy and structural adjustments timely have been able to seize
the opportunities and achieved significant economic progress at
different levels.
</P>
<P>
But, he pointed out that a majority of developing countries
have failed to reap their rightful benefits from globalization,
and some even face the danger of being adversely affected or even
marginalized.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that developed nations, as the biggest beneficiary
of globalization, should take more obligations and have unshirkable
responsibilities in helping developing countries to overcome
financial and debt difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The G77's ministerial meeting for Asian member states opened
on Monday, with a main purpose to prepare for the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) in 2000 in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 representatives, including over 10 ministers from
Asian countries, attended the four-day conference.
</P>
<P>
In addition to globalization, the participants will discuss
other topics, including private capital flows and instability in
the development process, debt problems, the international trading
system, information technology, governance of the globalizing
world economy.
</P>
<P>
The G77, which now has 133 member states, was established in
1964 by 77 developing countries at the end of the first session of
the UNCTAD in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
As the largest third world coalition in the U.N., the group
works on enhancing and promoting the collective interests of the
developing world and promoting economic and technical cooperation
among developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
