<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Again Denies Saudi Mad Cow Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government has denied claims in the Saudi Arabian press that South
African cattle are infected with mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
South African Agriculture and Land Affairs Minister Thoko
Didiza said Wednesday that the government had not been notified
officially by Saudi Arabia of the reason for its reported ban on
South African beef products.
</P>
<P>
She said her department was aware of previous attempts to deny
beef exports to Saudi Arabia for reasons that "could not be
scientifically justified".
</P>
<P>
The statement from the minister follows reports in the
Saudi-owned Asharq al-Aswat newspaper on Tuesday that Saudi Arabia
has imposed a ban on beef imports from South Africa because of
concerns over the disease.
</P>
<P>
Didiza said: "The South African government is investigating the
origin of and reasons for these irresponsible and unfounded
allegations."
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that South Africa was one of the first
countries to impose strict import requirements to prevent the
introduction of the mad cow disease when it was first discovered
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa has earned a respected status in the
international veterinary community for its attempts to control
animal diseases. This is the status we jealously protect in the
interest of our livestock industry, as we are free from the most
important trade sensitive diseases -- which includes official
freedom from foot and mouth disease and rinderpest."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Wednesday, the Foreign Affairs
Department said it supported Didiza's statement and called for
Saudi Arabia to raise the question "through appropriate channels".
</P>
<P>
The statement quoted Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad as
saying that relations with Saudi Arabia are very good and that if
Saudi Arabia was really concerned about the disease they would
have raised it with the South African authorities through the
appropriate channels.
</P>
<P>
"We are working with the Saudi authorities to urgently resolve
the matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pahad said there has never been a case of mad cow disease in
South Africa and that Pretoria is therefore surprised that some
unnamed official was reported to have made such allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
