<HEADLINE> Britain Urges India, Pakistan to Restore Mutual Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain urged India and Pakistan
to restore mutual trust on Wednesday after a war of words between
the two nuclear-armed neighbors was triggered by the downing of a
Pakistani patrol plane.
</P>
<P>
"We are deeply concerned by the incident yesterday in which a
Pakistani military aircraft was shot down with the loss of its
crew. We have instructed our high commissions in New Delhi and
Islamabad to urge their host governments to take immediate steps
to avoid further incidents and to restore mutual confidence and
trust," said Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made shortly after Hain held talks in London
with Pakistan's High Commissioner Mian Riaz Samee. The talks were
reportedly held at Samee's request.
</P>
<P>
An Indian MiG-21 fighter shot down a Pakistani reconnaissance
and anti-submarine aircraft on Tuesday, killing all 16 people
aboard.
</P>
<P>
India insisted the plane had intruded into its airspace, while
Pakistan denied the charge by saying the plane was shot down over
its own territory.
</P>
<P>
"This incident underlines the urgent need for India and
Pakistan to resolve their differences through dialogue," Hain said
in the statement. 
</P>
