<HEADLINE> HK's Leading Airline Reports Profits in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Cathay Pacific
Airways reported net profits of 108 million HK dollars (14 million
U.S. dollars) in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Turnover rose 1.4 percent to 13,167 million HK dollars (1,688
million U.S. dollars), while passenger numbers declined by 1
percent, according to the interim results announced by Cathay
Pacific Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that we have been able to return to
profitability after facing extremely challenging conditions
throughout 1998," said Cathay Pacific Chairman James Hughes-
Hallett.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific recorded a loss of 175 million HK dollars (22.4
million U.S. dollars) in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The first half of 1999 saw a recovery in a number of markets,
including the United States, Indonesia, South Korea and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The cargo services enjoyed a strong first half with turnover of
3,269 million HK dollars (419 million U.S. dollars), an 8.7
percent increase over the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific continued its fleet modernization plan during
the first half of the year, retiring five Boeing 747-300 aircraft
and taking delivery of two new B777-300s. The airline now has one
of the youngest fleets among major airlines.
</P>
<P>
It predicts that growing signs that key regional markets are
returning to positive economic growth should help the company's
performance over the remainder of this year.
</P>
<P>
"We still remain very confident about our long-term future and
the future of our home base Hong Kong," said Hughes-Hallett.
</P>
</TEXT>
