<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with Tibet Issue China Attaches Importance to Protection of Ethnic Minorities' Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- the Chinese government has
attached great importance to protecting the rights of the country'
s 55 ethnic minorities over the past 50 years, said a senior
Chinese official here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"China is a unified nation with many ethnic groups," said Qiao
Zonghuai, head of the Chinese Observer Delegation, during the 51st
session of a United Nations sub-commission on the promotion and
protection of human rights.
</P>
<P>
To maintain and develop relations of equality, unity and mutual
assistance among all ethnic groups, and to prohibit ethnic hatred
and discrimination, Qiao said the Chinese government has
formulated and implemented a series of effective policies, such as
the system of ethnic autonomy,
</P>
<P>
On the elimination of racial discrimination, he told the
meeting that "with great help from the central government, arduous
efforts by the ethnic people have substantially changed the
situation in ethnic regions, hence the enjoyment of human rights
by ethnic peoples has been remarkably improved."
</P>
<P>
The population of the 55 minority groups amounts to 108 million,
which accounts for 8.98% of the total population of China.
</P>
<P>
Qiao gave Tibet as an example which confirms that the Tibetan
people now can enjoy and exercise not only the whole range of
rights provided in the constitution but also various special
rights in accordance with the system of ethnic autonomy after they
shook off the oppression by the old Chinese government in the
Democratic Reform 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made great efforts to promote the
economic and social development in the Tibetan Autonomous Region
and protect the human rights of the Tibetan people, he said. The
religious freedom of the Tibetan people is respected and protected.
</P>
<P>
Since China adopted the policy of reform and opening-up, the
central government has allocated huge amount of money to renovate
and repair such religious sites as the Potala Palace and the
Jokhang Monastery.
</P>
<P>
The central government also attaches importance to the
protection of the rich traditional culture in Tibet and the
freedom of development of the Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet is an inalienable part of China, which is an
internationally recognized fact," Qiao pointed out. "Recently, a
few separatists, ignorant of the reality and fundamental changes
in Tibet, are attempting to split Tibet from china, in the so-
called pretext of 'protecting human rights' and seeking 'high
degree of autonomy'."
</P>
<P>
"This is strongly opposed by all the Chinese people including
the Tibetan people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qiao also told the meeting that his delegation fully endorses
the World Conference Against Racism and Racial Discrimination in
2001, which is now under preparation by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the parties concerned can reach an agreement on such
substantive matters as the function and agenda of the conference
and thus start the overall preparatory process," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
