<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Warned to Abide by Cease-fire Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Allied Forces Task Force in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) Wednesday warned the Congo
rebels to abide by the terms of the cease-fire agreement reached
in Lusaka on July 10, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The task force was quoted as saying in a statement from its
headquarters in Kinshasa that rebels and their allies continued to
attack their positions.
</P>
<P>
"The task force commander would like to warn the rebels and
their allies once again that his forces will respond decisively to
any further violations," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the rebels had attacked the Allied Forces
positions on August 8, 9 and 10, using artillery and small fire
arms.
</P>
<P>
The war in the Congo has since sucked in six African countries
which include Zimbabwe, Namibia, Angola and Chad on the side of
the Congolese government and Rwanda and Uganda supporting the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The major rebel group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy, could
not sign the Lusaka cease-fire agreement because of clashes from
within.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the statement said rebels continued to surrender to
the Allied Forces.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels are surrendering almost on daily basis in response
to the Congolese government amnesty," it said.
</P>
<P>
Congolese President Laurent Kabila offered the rebels an
amnesty soon after the signing of the Lusaka cease-fire agreement.
 
</P>
