<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rain Dampens Dreams of Eclipse Watchers in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- A unwelcomed heavy rain marred
the spectacle of long awaited solar eclipse here Wednesday, but
its occurrence was felt by the scary darkness in the sky at around
5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The sky along with heavy downpour and gusty winds became so
dark that the lights were turned on at home and on roads. However,
sunlight was restored when the rain ended at around 6:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
However, majority of the people watched the celestial drama on
their television screens, which was telecast live from Karachi,
Pakistan's biggest city on its southern coastline, and other two
cities through occasional breaks in the thick clouds.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse lasted for about two hours from 4:18 p.m. to 6:27
p.m. in Karachi. For around 1 minute 13 seconds, at 5:27 p.m., the
sun was totally obscured, appearing as a dark disc with a blazing
golden halo.
</P>
<P>
As the moon inched its way across the face of the sun, many
faithful offered special eclipse prayers at home and at mosques,
and prayed for two hours, while alms were distributed.
</P>
<P>
According to reports here, thick clouds blanketed much of the
country in the afternoon too, depriving many people of the rare
chance to see the last solar eclipse of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers said total eclipse occurs somewhere in the world
about every 18 months. However, this eclipse was unique as it
passed over the thickly populated areas of the world: traveling
across France, Germany, Yugoslavia, Romania, Turkey, Iraq and
Iran, Pakistan and India, before ending in a sunset in the Bay of
Bengal about two hours after its start.
</P>
<P>
After passing over Europe and the Middle East, it entered
Pakistan, plunging Karachi and nearby areas into darkness for more
than one minute.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of the country had been expected to witness a
partial eclipse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Nuclear Body Chief to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty Organization (CTBTO)
Wolfgang Hoffmann will visit South Africa from Thursday, South
Africa's Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his six-day visit, Hoffmann will meet senior government
officials and role-players in the nuclear field to share
information on the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
and acknowledge South Africa's role in the CTBT process where the
country is playing a leading role, the ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was among the first countries to sign and ratify
the CTBT, which was adopted by the United Nations General Assembly
on September 10, 1996.
</P>
<P>
South Africa ratified the treaty on March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Under Article 1 of the CTBT, each state party "undertakes not
to carry out any nuclear-weapons test explosion or any other
nuclear explosion, and to prohibit and prevent any such nuclear
explosion at any place under its jurisdiction or control."
</P>
<P>
The need for a treaty of this nature, was highlighted when
India and Pakistan consecutively conducted nuclear tests during
May 1999, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Adoption of the CTBT by the international community means an
end to nuclear tests globally and is a welcome umbrella in
addition to the advances made on the African continent by the
overwhelming support given to the African Nuclear Weapon Free Zone
-- the Pelindaba Treaty," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
