<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Gun Owners Protest Gun-control Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,200 protesters
took to the streets in Cape Town Wednesday in a march against
government proposals for a tougher law on gun ownership.
</P>
<P>
The march -- organized by Victims Against Crime, United
Christian Action and the South African Gunowners Association --
took place in front of Parliament, where the protesters handed a
memorandum to a representative of the national department of
safety and security.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum, addressed to Safety and Security Minister Steve
Tshwete, rejected the "irresponsible, excessive and intrusive"
requirements of the draft Firearms Control Bill, expected to come
before Parliament in the current session, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The memo said the bill would effectively outlaw nine out of
every ten licensed firearms, restrict people to owning only one
handgun and 100 rounds, raise license fees to 500 rand (80 U.S.
dollars) renewable every five years at ministerial discretion, and
place "arbitrary" restrictions on barrel length, maximum calibre
and magazine capacity.
</P>
<P>
Self-defense would also no longer be an acceptable reason for
owning a firearm, said the memo.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum said the bill should be scrapped as its only
effect would be to increase violence and crime.
</P>
<P>
It expressed concern at the "secretive and underhand" way the
bill had been drafted and asked why the drafters had ignored the
expertise, experience and advice of firearms experts such as the
South African Gunowners Association.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum pointed out that the vast majority of the
estimated four to nine million illegal firearms in the country
were not stolen from legal owners, but smuggled in from
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The ministry itself had reported to Parliament that incidents
of crime committed by registered firearm owners were statistically
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
"As licensed firearm owners are not the problem, why target
them with such laborious, time and money-wasting demands?"
</P>
<P>
Gun control would not end the violence, but rather disarm
potential victims, the memo noted.
</P>
<P>
"Every day in South Africa, hundreds of crimes are prevented,
hundreds of victims are protected, and countless tragedies averted
by armed citizens," it said.
</P>
<P>
It called for a new drafting committee including
representatives of Victims Against Crime, United Christian Action
and the South African Gunowners Association.
</P>
<P>
African Christian Democratic Party (ACDP) MP Steve Swart told
the marchers at Parliament that the ACDP supported the protest and
would oppose all attempts by government to disarm law-abiding
citizens.
</P>
<P>
"The role of government should be to disarm criminals and
confiscate illegal weapons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, it appeared that the aim of the bill was to disarm
those people who had licensed firearms and to make it more
difficult to legally obtain firearms in future.
</P>
<P>
"Government needs to prevent a scenario where obtaining a
firearm illegally is easier and cheaper than obtaining one
legally," Swart said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
