<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Set for Further Fall, Says UK Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) - British inflation looks set to
fall still further, despite the pick-up in the economic recovery,
the Bank of England said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank said the immediate
outlook is for growth with low inflation. But it acknowledged
there is "considerable uncertainty" over prospects for the future.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor Mervyn King said no one could claim to know
exactly where inflation was going in the longer term and that
opinion was divided among the members of the Bank's Monetary
Policy Committee (MPC).
</P>
<P>
But he expected underlying inflation to fall below 2 percent
over the next "year or so", before rising slightly above the
government's 2.5 percent target in two years' time.
</P>
<P>
Official figures released recently showed that average earnings
were up 4.4 percent in June well above the rate of inflation and
unemployment down to 4.3 percent, its lowest level since March
1980.
</P>
<P>
Both of these factors could contribute to inflationary
pressures, along with the rapid heating up of the housing market.
</P>
<P>
The Bank's base rate has fallen sharply over the past twelve
months and now stands at 5 percent, the lowest figure for more
than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The report released Wednesday was interpreted by economists
here as indicating the next move in British interest rates by the
Bank's MPC will be upwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
