<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Unemployment at 19-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) - The number of people out of work
in Britain dropped by 32,900 in July to 1,236,300, taking the
jobless rate to 4.3 percent, a new 19-year low, Official figures
showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The monthly fall figure was much bigger than the markets were
expecting - predictions had put the figure at about 5,000.
</P>
<P>
One labor market analyst said: "It is an extremely strong
report, highlighting the tightness of the labor market and clearly
highlights inflation risks."
</P>
<P>
Another said: "I am surprised the figure has moved so much. It
does underline the fact that it has been an extremely soft
landing. This is very bad news."
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics added average earnings
growth ticked up to 4.4 percent in the three months to June from
4.3 percent in May, well above the expected 4.1 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed here that the slump in the number of
people claiming unemployment benefit highlighted the inflationary
risks in the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
