<HEADLINE> Appointed Officials of Future Macao SAR Show Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The newly appointed officials of
the future Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) have said
that they will meet new challenges and make concerted efforts with
the chief executive of the SAR to build a better Macao.
</P>
<P>
The State Council of China on Wednesday announced the
appointment of seven leading officials of the first government of
the Macao SAR and the SAR's procurator-general in accordance with
the nomination of Edmund Ho Hau Wah, chief executive-designate of
the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Florinda da Rosa Silva Chan, who was appointed secretary for
administration and justice, told reporters late Wednesday that she
and other officials of the SAR will show team spirit and exert the
greatest efforts to serve the SAR and local residents.
</P>
<P>
"The civil servants of the SAR will surely meet the high
expectations of the residents with high morale, efficient work and
better transparency," she said.
</P>
<P>
Florinda also noted that some Portuguese law specialists will
remain in the civil service of the future SAR government.
</P>
<P>
Francis Tam Pak Yuen, a businessman-turned official to take
charge of economic and financial affairs, said the he was ready to
shoulder more responsibility for the society and he would do his
best at his future post.
</P>
<P>
"I'm prepared to quit from all my business management, and my
family members will have to sacrifice their personal interests to
some extent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Francis Tam vowed that the future SAR government will abide by
the "one country, two systems" principle, ensure a free market
economy and display Macao's advantages so that the local economy
can step out of the current depression and regain vitality.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the finance conditions in the future, the SAR
government will consider the establishment of a fiscal reserve
system in response to the appeal of the local residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Chui Sai On, who was appointed secretary for social
and cultural affairs, told the media that he would try his utmost
to help the chief executive upgrade the life of local residents.
</P>
<P>
"Social and cultural affairs are closely related to people's
varied aspects of life. Therefore, the SAR government will make
overall assessment of relevant work and map out detailed policy,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Chui noted that the SAR government will improve
medical care so that old people will be looked after better and
patients will receive better treatment.
</P>
<P>
Ao Man Long, as secretary for transportation and public
projects, said that the SAR government will plan infrastructure
projects which help boost economy, increase consumption, create
jobs, and enhance contacts with surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Being appointed commissioner against corruption, Cheong U said
that he was ready to meet new challenges and would turn Macao into
a clean and efficient society.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chio Meng, appointed procurator-general, expressed his
confidence that the procuratorate of the SAR will strive to
exercise its independent function to ensure law-enforcement.
</P>
<P>
The other two officials of the Macao SAR government, Cheong
Kuok Va, secretary for security, and Fatima Choi Mei Lei, director
of audit, were not in Macao for the interviews. 
</P>
</TEXT>
