<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Parliament Approves Loan for DPRK Nuclear Reactors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Parliament
Thursday approved a loan of 3.22 billion U.S. dollars for two
light-water nuclear reactors for the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Under the loan agreement, passed in the single-chamber National
Assembly unanimously Thursday, South Korea will provide 3.22
billion dollars to the Korean Peninsula Energy Development
Organization (KEDO) to cover 70 percent of the reactor project's
budget, while Japan will pay 1 billion dollars and the United
States will provide the balance.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK will repay the 4.6 billion dollars project's cost over
20 years after a 3-year grace period once the plants are completed
in 2003. Construction on the power plant began in August 1997 in
Kumho, a village on the DPRK's northeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
KEDO was established on March 9, 1995, by the United States,
Japan and South Korea, according to a 1994 agreement between
Washington and Pyongyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
