<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary At 1520 GMT, August 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain said Thursday that NATO's commander in Kosovo,
British Lieutenant-General Mike Jackson, is to be moved up to full
general next year.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry spokesman said the veteran soldier will
become commander-in-chief of Land Command next March.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Jackson, 55, is expected to complete his tenure as the
commander of peacekeeping force for Kosovo, known as KFOR, in
Kosovo in October. (Britain-Jackson-Promotion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's Diet (parliament) Thursday enacted a set of
bills that will allow investigators to wiretap communications to
fight organized crime, despite last-ditch efforts by opposition
parties to block their passage.
</P>
<P>
The package includes a bill allowing law enforcement
authorities to wiretap private communications to investigate
crimes involving drugs, guns, murders committed by groups, and the
mass smuggling of people into Japan. (Japan-Wiretapping)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Defense Minister George Fernandes said
Thursday he did not visualize any threat from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the two countries were on the brink of war,
particularly because both have nuclear weapons, he said he was not
worried about the two being nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
"But," he stressed, "we are not on the brink of war" and "
everything is in control." (India-Pakistan-No Threat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian security forces will launch a "massive
operation" against Islamic rebels in Daghestan in the coming days,
Deputy Interior Minister Igor Zubov said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian military intends to do away with Islamic guerrilla
groups hiding in mountainous Daghestan within an "established time
frame," Zubov said.  (Russia-Daghestan-Operation) 
</P>
