<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Enacts Laws to Protect Local Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada signed into law Thursday two measures aimed at protecting
local industries from unfair trade practices brought about by the
entry of subsidized and cheap imports into the country.
</P>
<P>
The president signed Republic Act No. 8751 aimed at
strengthening the imposition of countervailing duties on imported
subsidized products, including agricultural goods.
</P>
<P>
Under this act, countervailing duties will be slapped on
imported subsidized articles that may cause the "material injury,"
"material retardation of the growth," or "the prevention of the
establishment" of an affected domestic industry.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also signed the Anti-Dumping Act of 1999, which
provides rules on the imposition of duties on cheap, imported
goods that threaten domestic industries producing the same
products.
</P>
<P>
This act was signed into law primarily to stop the importation
of cheap, usually substandard products that flood the local market
and threaten domestic goods.
</P>
<P>
It provides for a shorter, simplified and more systematic
process of investigating cases of dumping in the country and
penalizes officials who fail to undertake the necessary actions
against dumping as required under the law.
</P>
<P>
"We believe in free trade, but we also insist on fair trade,"
the president said at the signing ceremony held at the
Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
He said the Philippines, being a founding member of the World
Trade Organization, is firmly committed to opening its markets,
engaging in free trade to make the economy globally competitive.
</P>
<P>
"But our markets are open to those prepared to compete with our
industries on a level playing field, not in underhanded games or
through underground methods," the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
