<HEADLINE> U.S. Bumper Harvest Projected Despite Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. farmers will reap a
bumper harvest of corn, soybeans, rice and other crops despite the
drought and heat that have plagued parts of the country this
summer, the Agriculture Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Soybean production is forecast to reach a record high 2.9
billion bushels, up 4 percent from last year, although the drought
has ruined crops from Ohio through the mid-Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
The corn harvest is expected to be the third largest on record
at 9.6 billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
Most of the nation's heartland has received plenty of rain this
summer and a Midwest heat wave eased in time to spare most crops,
DPA279HAB206I12TEQL23:2823:291945
the Agriculture Department said.
</P>
<P>
The department expected a modest increase in prices for some
commodities -- 20 cents a bushel for soybeans and 5 cents a bushel
for corn -- because of tightening world supplies or rising
exports. The average price of corn is expected to range from 1.70
to 2.10 U.S. dollars this year while soybean prices average 4.10
to 4.90 dollars per bushel.
</P>
<P>
The higher prices could save the government as much as 1
billion dollars in crop subsidies, but many farmers still wouldn't
recover their cost of production. The Senate last week approved a
7.4 billion dollar package of farm assistance; the House has yet
to act.
</P>
<P>
The biggest impact of the drought could be on dairy farmers.
Milk prices are expected to rise as much as 50 cents per hundred
pounds because of strong demand for cheese and declining
production in the parched Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Cotton production is expected to be up by a third from last
year when there was a severe drought across the South.
DPA280HAB207I12TEQL23:2923:290711
</P>
<P>
The rice crop is expected to be a record 21 billion pounds, up
12 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
Wheat production is down 9 percent, as many farmers switched to
other crops they thought would be more lucrative this year. But
world wheat stocks are rising because of a big crop in China this
year, so the Agriculture Department doesn't expect prices to
increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
