<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Falls to Six-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The exchange rate of the
Philippine peso to the U.S. dollar depreciated Thursday to
six-month low of 39.225 pesos from Wednesday's 39.15 pesos with
the turnover volume of 305.4 million dollars transacted at the
Philippine Dealing System.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the depreciation to the low peso yields
which pushes investors to shift more funds into dollar investment,
triggering heavy dollar-buying on the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, external factors such as solid fears about a hike in
U.S. interest rates added more pressure on the currency.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafael Buenaventura, governor of the Philippine
Central Bank, said that the peso-dollar rate is still on the
"tolerable level" and the central bank will not intervene.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said earlier that the peso's
weakness was not justified given the country's sound economic
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said that the drop in the peso was temporary and would
reverse as the country's foreign loans start coming in. The
government is expecting about 900 million dollars in various loan
inflows.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the year, the central bank has cut its key
interest rates by 437.5 basis points, bringing the overnight
borrowing rate to 9.0 percent and overnight lending rate to 11.0
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
