<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Rise 0.7 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
reported Thursday that retail sales in July picked up unexpected
0.7 percent, pushed by a big increase in automotive sales.
</P>
<P>
The Department said total retail sales rose last month to a
seasonally adjusted 248.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The July advance followed a revised 0.2 percent decline in
June. The 0.7 percent increase is better than many analysts had
expected. Many analysts had been forecasting a gain of 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales, which represent about a third of the nation's
economic output, have climbed or held steady most months of this
year and were 9.1 percent higher than July of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter of the year, consumer spending continues
to remain brisk. With unemployment near a three-decade low, growth
in wages and benefits and a strong stock market, consumers are
continuing to feel confident.
</P>
<P>
Last month, sales at automobile dealerships rose a sizable 2.3
percent, following a decrease of 0.8 percent in June. The auto
industry expects to have a record year of sales in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Without the volatile autos category, retail sales still would
have risen 0.3 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline sales also jumped 1.2 percent in July, following a
drop of 0.5 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices had reached their highest point in more than 18
months in July partly because of production cuts by the
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, as well as
recovering Asian and Latin American economies. However, in recent
weeks, gas prices have been moderating.
</P>
<P>
Sales of durable goods increased a solid 1.6 percent in July,
after being down 0.9 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
Sales of nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, rose 0.2
percent in July, following a 0.4 percent gain the month before.
</P>
<P>
Sales at food stores rose a tiny 0.1 percent in July, after
having dropped the month before. But sales at grocery stores held
steady for the second month in a row.
</P>
<P>
However, at apparel and accessory shops, sales fell 0.4 percent
in July, matching 0.4 percent drop the month before. And, sales at
bar and restaurants also fell by 0.4 percent in July, following a
0.2 percent gain the month before.
</P>
<P>
Last week, most chain stores reported that their retail sales
topped expectations in July, helped out by a strong U.S. economy
and a heat wave in much of the country that sent people to
air-conditioned stores. The big winners in July were the discount
chains, as shoppers turned to stores like Wal-Mart, Target and
Kmart for a wide selection and affordable prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0069 </DOCNO>
