<HEADLINE> Philippines to Raise Oil Prices Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A ranking official of the
Philippine government confirmed Thursday that the prices of
petroleum products in the country will be raised next month as the
price of crude oil in the world market has risen to 19 U.S.
dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Cyril de Callar, undersecretary of the Department of Energy
(DOE), said the price increase will push through despite the worry
that the oil price hike will have a direct impact on the prices of
commodity goods in the market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Callar said that the government is doing its best to
closely monitor and check oil companies to ensure that they are
not selling their petroleum products based on the old importation
price for huge profits.
</P>
<P>
He said the DOE is calling on the oil firms not to cheat the
consumers by effecting a new price increase on the old stocks of
petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
Callar confirmed that the oil companies still have stocks that
could last for 60 days' supply so that any increase now would be
tantamount to economic sabotage.
</P>
<P>
He said that every week, the DOE requires these oil firms to
submit to the government a report on their oil inventory and
latest importation records in order to find out if they are indeed
taking advantage of the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
