<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Doctors Turning Gray, Health Institute Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada is seeing its pool of 56,
203 physicians grow steadily older, with 22 percent of them
between the ages of 50 and 59, the Canadian Institute for Health
Information said.
</P>
<P>
The number is impressive compared to 18 percent of the total
number of physicians practicing in 1993, the Institute reported.
It also warned Wednesday of a shortage of doctors in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
The institute indicated a downward trend in the number of young
doctors in the country under the age of 40, claiming that they
made up only 29 percent of the total last year compared to 36.6
percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The institute, which is an independent health organization,
attributes the phenomenon partly to a relatively large exodus of
young practitioners to the United States earlier this decade.
</P>
<P>
It is also critical of a "short-sighted" decision by the
federal and provincial governments to severely limit the number of
practicing Canadian physicians.
</P>
<P>
The institute's warning comes days before the Canadian medical
Association will open its annual meeting here later this month.
</P>
<P>
The medical association has already estimated that there will
be only one doctor for every 718 patients in 2021, unless
something is done to increase the number of physicians.
</P>
<P>
Last year's medical statistics showed that there was only one
doctor for every 548 patients.
</P>
<P>
The medical association meeting is expected to urge a dramatic
increase in the number of students allowed into Canadian medical
schools and teaching hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
