<HEADLINE> Barmasai May be Disqualified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- World 3,000 meters steeplechase
record holder Bernard Barmasai, one of the four athletes to win
the Golden League one million US dollars jackpot, could be
disqualified, an IAAF spokesman said Thursday in Zurich,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan admitted Wednesday that he asked compatriot
Christopher Koskei to slow down before the finish of the race in
Wednesday's Weltklasse meet before he won the race by one stride
ahead of Koskei.
</P>
<P>
The win kept Barmasai in the chase of the season-ending million
US dollars jackpot for athletes who win all the seven meets of the
Golden League.
</P>
<P>
"His (Koskei's) last 100 meters are really good," said Barmasai.
"When he tried to pass I tried to talk to him. I said 'leave it
for me', and that's why he slowed down. He would have won today,
but because he is a friend and we have to live together...the
jackpot is for me and my friends."
</P>
<P>
The International Amateur Athletic Federation announced
Thursday that it would formally investigate "to ensure that the
principles of fair play have been fully respected."
</P>
<P>
International Amateur Athletic Federation spokesman Giorgio
Reineri said if the case turned out to be a misunderstanding then
no action would be taken, but if it was true then: "In this case,
it's obvious there is the disqualification of the athlete."
</P>
<P>
If Barmasai lost, American sprint-queen Marion Jones, Romanian
middle-distance specialist Gabriela Szabo and Denmark's 800-metre
world record holder Wilson Kipketer would suit to a three split of
the jackpot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
