<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Countries Call for Cooperation Among </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Asian economic ministers
Thursday called on developing countries to strengthen cooperation
to face the challenges in the process of globalization.
</P>
<P>
After a four-day discussion at the ministerial meeting of the
Asian member states of the Group 77 (G77), 25 ministers issued a
common statement.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the ministers emphasized the importance of
economic cooperation among developing countries as a strategy for
development and the common prosperity of the region.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation has become all the more relevant in the face
of the challenges of a globalizing world economy, they said.
</P>
<P>
They noted that trade among developing countries has expanded
significantly; intra-regional foreign direct investment by
developing countries in Asia has increased substantially; and
sub-regional economic cooperation initiatives are playing an
increasing important role in regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
The ministers called for strengthening cooperation among
developing countries in international negotiations on trade,
monetary and financial matters with a view to enhancing their
development objectives.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed an exchange of experiences in the light of
the recent Asian financial crisis, called for the establishment of
a working group to recommend actions and suggest policy proposals
regarding mechanisms for crisis management and prevention.
</P>
<P>
The G77's ministerial meeting for Asian member states opened
on Monday. It is held to brace Asian countries for the 10th
session of the United Nations Conference on Trade and Development
(UNCTAD) in 2000 in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 representatives from Asian countries and international
organizations attended the session.
</P>
<P>
In addition to globalization, the participants also discussed
other topics, including private capital flows and instability in
the development process, debt problems, the international trading
system, information technology, governance of the globalizing
world economy.
</P>
<P>
The G77, which now has 133 member states, was established in
1964 by 77 developing countries at the end of the first session of
the UNCTAD in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
As the largest third world coalition in the U.N., the group
works on enhancing and promoting the collective interests of the
developing world and promoting economic and technical cooperation
between developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
