<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Agrees to More U.N. Police in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Thursday approved U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
proposal of increasing the number of U.N. civilian police and
military liaison officers after the U.N.-supervised direct ballot
in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"The additional U.N. civilian police and military liaison
officers will have the same position and function as the present
U.N. civilian police and military liaison officers. There will be
no change of function," Foreign Minister Ali Alatas told reporters
after accompanying Habibie in a meeting with U.N. secretary
general's special envoy for East Timor Jamsheed Marker here.
</P>
<P>
Alatas reiterated that what Jakarta agreed to is the addition
of U.N. civilian police personnel, not an addition to their
functions or duties.
</P>
<P>
"The civilian police will be civilian police, and military
liaison officers will always be military liaison officers. They
will never become a peacekeeping force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his meeting with Habibie, Marker said they
discussed a range of topics on East Timor. But he refused to give
details.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot tell you before I report it to the secretary
general," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan in his report to the U.N. Security Council Tuesday
recommended that additional U.N. civilian police and military
liaison officers be sent to East Timor after the direct ballot on
August 30.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard, the number of U.N.
civilian police will become 460, including 50 members from the
local population, up from 280 proposed before.
</P>
<P>
The military liaison officers will be bolstered to 300 from the
present 50 and they will act as mediators among the military, the
pro-integration militia and the anti-integration group.
</P>
<P>
The August 30 ballot will allow the territory's people to
choose whether their homeland should become an autonomous region
within Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
