<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians to Vote on Republic on November 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Australians will vote on a
republic on November 6 after parliament Thursday night passed the
republic referendum bill and a preamble to the country's
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Both the bill setting up the republic referendum question and
the bill for Prime Minister John Howard's compromise preamble for
the constitution passed the Senate Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
They were approved earlier by the House of Representatives and
have now passed parliament.
</P>
<P>
The republic referendum question is if the Australians agree
with "an Act to alter the Constitution to establish the
Commonwealth of Australia as a republic with the Queen and
governor-general being replaced by a president appointed by a
two-thirds majority of the members of the Commonwealth
parliament."
</P>
<P>
The bill of the proposed preamble, a deal reached by Prime
Minister John Howard and the Australian Democrats Wednesday, was
passed unamended.
</P>
<P>
The proposed preamble said the Australians honor "Aborigines
and Torres Strait Islanders, the nation's first people, for their
deep kinship with their lands and for their ancient and continuing
cultures which enrich the life of our country."
</P>
<P>
It ended the row over the recognition of Aborigines and Torres
Strait Islanders by referring to their "deep kinship" with the
land.
</P>
<P>
It also ditched the controversial reference of mateship to
Aborigines and Torres Strait Islanders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
