<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tripartite High-Level Meeting on E. Timor Kicks Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting on East Timor
among senior officials of Indonesia, Portugal and the United
Nations kicked off here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting is likely to discuss the political and
security issues that will arise after the U.N.-sponsored autonomy
ballot in East Timor is held on August 30.
</P>
<P>
Besides U.N. secretary-general's special envoy for East Timor
Jamsheed Marker, the U.N. delegation consists of Ian Martin, chief
of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET), Francesc Vendrell,
Mono P. Bahgat, Joachim, Hutter and Tamrat Samuel.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian side is chaired by Nugroho Wisnumurti, director
general for political affairs of the Foreign Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese delegation is composed of Portuguese Ambassador
at Large Fernando Neves as chairman and Chief of Portugal's
interest section here Ana Gomes.
</P>
<P>
Neves told reporters shortly before the meeting that they will
discuss the second phase of the ballot in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He said they will also discuss the continued presence of the
United Nations in the territory after the vote to enable it to
handle the interim period during the implementation of the ballot
result.
</P>
<P>
The participants are expected to issue a joint communique on
the results of their discussions on the last day of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N.-brokered agreement with Portugal, Indonesia agreed
to hold the direct ballot on August 30, which will allow the
territory's people to choose whether their homeland should become
an autonomous region within Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
