<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factional Fighting Kills 15 in Somali Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 15 people were
killed and 17 others wounded Thursday morning in a heavy fighting
between factions for the control of the town of Bur Dhubo in
southern Somalia, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The reports indicated that the mainstream forces of the Somali
National Front (SNF) led by General Omar Hajji Masalleh took the
town from the SNF breakaway faction loyal to Ahmed Sheikh Buraleh.
</P>
<P>
The exact casualties are not known. However, radio operators
outside the town confirmed that 15 people were killed and more
than 17 others wounded during the heavy exchange of gunfire for
control of the town which is about 35 kms southeast of the
regional capital Garbaharrey.
</P>
<P>
SNF mainstream spokesman Ibrahim Jama Howleh also confirmed the
 fighting by claiming a victory against what he called the
Ethiopian- supported split faction of Buraleh.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman declared that his forces have taken control of
the town after inflicting heavy losses on the troops of Buraleh,
adding that his forces have confiscated large amount of ammunition
and telecommunication equipment.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports indicated that situation in the town now is
calm, but tense.
</P>
<P>
The VHF radios are once again on the air carrying out business
messages as well as other information regarding the situation of
the town and the families looking for each other.
</P>
<P>
Buraleh's fighters supported by dozens of battle wagons from
the Ethiopian forces had driven Masalleh's militiamen out of Bur
Dhubo town in late June this year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the forces of Masalleh mounted attacks
after the Ethiopian forces withdrew from the town following the
unrest of Bulo Hawo town Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SNF spokesman admitted that eight of their fighters were
killed during the armed confrontation for control of the town
while more than five others have sustained gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
Howleh also claimed that his men had killed nine soldiers and
wounded seven others from the other side while also capturing six
prisoners of war from Buraleh's men.
</P>
<P>
There's no word as yet from the others side led by Buraleh.
</P>
<P>
However, independent sources confirmed the fall of the town to
the SNF faction of Masalleh.
</P>
<P>
The sources also suggested that the defeated fighters of
Buraleh had retreated back to Luq town, the former Al-Itihad
Al-Islam headquarters but now controlled by the Ethiopian forces
that support the loyalists of Buraleh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
