<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth of Money Supply Slightly Slower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released today by the
People's Bank of China (PBOC) show that China's financial sector
maintained smooth operations in July but the growth of money
supply slowed some what.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of broad money (M2)
stood at 11.14 trillion yuan, up 15.7 percent from the same period
last year, while that of narrow money (M1) was 3.9 trillion yuan,
up 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The growth speed of both broad money and narrow money slowed
slightly compared with the previous month, which was considered a
short-term phenomenon caused by capital diversion to stock markets.
The growth of broad money should still be above 17 percent when
deducting this factor, according to a spokesman for the PBOC.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of all loans by
financial institutions was 9.12 trillion yuan, up 14.6 percent.
The first seven months saw increased loans of 476.9 billion yuan,
an increase of 24 billion yuan over that of the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Of the increased loans, 43.3 billion yuan went to the
industrial sector, 46.1 billion yuan went to agriculture while 104.
6 billion yuan was put into infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
By the end of July, the outstanding amount of all deposits in
financial institutions was 10.29 trillion yuan, up 16.2 percent,
of which individual deposits accounted for 5.92 trillion yuan, up
16.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the end of July, the exchange rate of the Renminbi yuan was
one US dollar to 8.2774 RMB yuan, up 13 basic points from that at
the end of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
