<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Stop Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Thursday urged African governments to advance the vision of
a world without war by preventing conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe was addressing hundreds of people who had gathered
outside his office at Munhumutapa Building in Harare to mark the
Defense Forces Day.
</P>
<P>
The president said it was in pursuit of that vision that
Zimbabwe had sent troops to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
to defend the government of President Laurent Kabila against
rebels aided by neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"Other continents cannot be expected to have a zeal and
enthusiasm to come to the assistance of Africa if Africans
themselves do not have the commitment to help themselves," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the joint operation of the allied forces in the Congo
sends signals that the region was ready to consolidate democracy
on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad sent troops to the Congo
last year to ward off attacks from rebels backed by Uganda and
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the efforts by the allied countries to send troops
to the Congo should not be misconstrued to mean they had
territorial ambitions.
</P>
<P>
"Our efforts in Mozambique, Somalia, Angola, Rwanda and lately
the DRC must be seen continentally and internationally as
worthwhile for the cause of peaceful and beneficial co-existence
of mankind," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe had intervened in the former Zaire because it
recognized the norms of peace and stability as enshrined in its
defense policy.
</P>
<P>
He also said the expected presence of an Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Joint Military Commission and a United Nations
peace-keeping force in the Congo would create an environment for
socio-economic rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries involved in the conflict signed a
cease-fire agreement in Lusaka on July 10, which paved the way for
the two international bodies to intervene in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also pledged that his government will continue to
resolve operational impediments facing the defense forces.
</P>
<P>
He said the efforts to upgrade the forces' fighting capability
through the procurement of equipment would continue to receive
serious attention from the government.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the unfavorable macro-economic environment was
making it extremely difficult for the Defense Ministry to improve
the general conditions of the armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
