<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telecom , SingTel Negotiate for Alliance or Equity Deal: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Europe's top phone company
Deutsche Telekom (DT) is negotiating with Singapore
Telecommunications (SingTel) for either setting up an alliance or
taking 20 percent of SingTel's stake, local media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They quoted German magazine Wirtschafts Woche as saying
Wednesday that talks between Deutsche Telekom chairman Ron Sommer
and SingTel president and chief executive officer Lee Hsien Yang
are already "underway".
</P>
<P>
Lee was also quoted by the magazine as saying that DT's stake
purchase would benefit SingTel "as it would be able to compete
internationally."
</P>
<P>
Local media said though SingTel spokesman Ivan Tan declined to
comment on what he described as "speculation", the possibility of
a deal could not be ruled out as the company's standard practice
in the past has been to deny outright rumors which had no basis
while keeping mum on ongoing negotiations.
</P>
<P>
But local media quoted an anonymous source as saying it
appeared unlikely at this point in time that DT would take an
equity stake in SingTel.
</P>
<P>
However, local English newspaper The Straits Times gave out
another version of the story.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an unidentified source as saying that SingTel and DT
are exploring the possibility of setting up a billion-dollar joint
venture company which will pool their Asian cellular assets.
</P>
<P>
The two are in early stage of talks to combine their regional
mobile phone assets for greater synergy.
</P>
<P>
SingTel, which has stated publicly its intention to link up all
its Asian cellular investments to offer customers greater services
enhancement, has a 20 percent stake in Thailand's Advanced
Info-Service, and a 40 percent shareholding in Philippine firm
Globe Telecom, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
SingTel's German counterpart has a 10 percent stake in Isla
Communications of the Philippines and a 25 percent stake in PT
Satelindo of Indonesia, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the source as saying that such an alliance
would boost companies' vision of becoming leading carriers in Asia
since it would result in economies of scale and improved
operational efficiency.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper quoted another source as saying that there
are hurdles that need to be overcome for such an alliance to
succeed and it was premature to say an alliance was definitely in
the offing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
