<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks Myanmar to Help Fight Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has asked the Myanmar
government to help curb the influx of illicit drugs into the
country, the Thai News Agency (TNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
One of the measures to be discussed by the two governments is
the establishment of a border checkpoint to block narcotic
transportation between Myanmar's Myawaddy and Thailand's Tak
province in the north, TNA quoted Minister to the Prime Minister's
Office Jurin Laksanavisit as saying.
</P>
<P>
TNA said that Jurin had sent the message to Rangoon through the
Myanmar ambassador to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Jurin, who oversees the country's Office of the Narcotics
Control Board, said that he will also discuss with Myanmar
officials a plan to train Myanmar personnel in the detection of
chemicals used in narcotic production.
</P>
<P>
A joint meeting of senior anti-narcotic officials from both
Thailand and Myanmar is expected to be held in Thailand's southern
province of Ranong on August 17-18 to discuss comprehensive
measures to fight illicit drug trafficking along the border.
</P>
<P>
According to Jurin, about 80 percent of illicit drugs smuggled
into Thailand were produced by the anti-Rangoon Red Wa Army which
was situated in border areas of Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
