<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Check-up Ordered for Canadian Troops in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Chief of Defense Staff
Maurice Baril has ordered medical examinations for 3,000 Canadian
military personnel deployed in the Balkans between 1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The "Ottawa Citizen" newspaper said Thursday that orders were
sent to regional military commanders Monday in a bid to defuse the
scandal over possible contamination of soldiers serving in Croatia
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Overlapping investigations are being conducted to determine
whether or not the Canadian troops were exposed to contaminated
soil, which was alleged to be bauxite, which is used as material
for military works.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said someone from high-ranking sources ordered
the removal of a January 1995 letter from soldiers' files that
underscored their possible exposure to toxins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
