<HEADLINE> Li Hongzhi's Role in Illegal Gathering at Zhongnanhai (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li's return to Beijing was well planned. He notified Ji Liewu,
a key member of the Research Society of Falun Dafa, in advance. As
soon as Li returned to his Beijing residence in Chongwen District,
Ji came to report the circumstances about Falun Gong practitioners
besieging Tianjin Teachers University.
</P>
<P>
That this siege was the first thing Li was eager to learn about
shows that from the very beginning he wanted to plot an even
larger incident out of Tianjin gathering.
</P>
<P>
A magazine sponsored by Tianjin Teachers University published
an article on Qigong written by He Zuoxiu, academician of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), in early April.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his ideas about Qigong with the use of facts,
questioning a piece of Falun Gong propaganda which claimed that
after practicing Falun Gong, an engineer was able to go into a
working steel-smelting furnace and see with his own eyes the
chemical changes occurring at the atomic and molecular level.
</P>
<P>
He, an academician with China's top natural sciences research
body, also gave as an example a student at the CAS Institute of
Theoretical Physics with whom He is working.
</P>
<P>
The student had to be sent to a mental facility twice after
refusing to eat, drink, or sleep, or speak to anyone after
practicing Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Falun Gong including Li Hongzhi saw He Zuoxiu's
article published by the Tianjin Teachers University magazine with
a limited circulation as an opportunity to make trouble.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, a massive number of Falun Gong practitioners burst
into Tianjin Teachers University, staging a sit-in demonstration,
and completely disrupting the normal teaching and living
activities at the university.
</P>
<P>
In May 1998, Beijing Television Station was besieged for
several days by more than 1,000 Falun Gong practitioners because
the station broadcast a program unfavorable to Falun Gong.
</P>
