<HEADLINE> China's Development Zones Attract US$28 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's 32 economic and
technological development zones have used a total of 28 billion U.
S. dollars of overseas investment funds since 1984, accounting for
one-tenth of the country's total, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the foreign exchange earned by the development zones
amounted to 10.6 billion U.S. dollars, according to the sixth
annual conference on investment and development in China's
economic and technological development zones, which ended today in
this capital of southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
A total of 113 multinational corporations have invested in the
development zones, with contractual use of foreign funds standing
at 50.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that 60 percent of overseas-funded
projects in China are concentrated in the development zones.
</P>
<P>
The Dalian Economic and Technological Development Zone, the
first of its kind approved by the Chinese government, has approved
1,200 overseas-funded enterprises since 1984, with an actual use
of overseas funds amounting to nearly 2.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Economic and Technological Development Zone has
approved 140 overseas-funded enterprises since it was founded in
1993. Exports by operational overseas-funded enterprises in the
zone totaled 66 million U.S. dollars-worth in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
