<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spends More on Technological Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China increased the funding for
scientific and technological development to 103.3 yuan per capita
in 1998, 7.7 yuan more than in 1997, official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint report issued by the National Bureau of
Statistics (NBS) and the Ministry of Science and Technology here
today, the average expenditure per scientific and technological
worker in 1998 was 44,000 yuan, 4,000 yuan more than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
An NBS official said that China increased its input into
scientific and technological promotion steadily last year, with
the treasury increasing spending and local companies investing
more heavily in the development of new products.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that spending on science and technology by
local governments saw a diminishing growth rate last year, and
that funding for research and development grew more slowly than in
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China's funding for scientific and technological advances
totaled 128.98 billion yuan last year, while actual spending in
this respect was 112.85 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that government spending on science and
technology accounts for 4.3 percent of total budget expenditures
last year, the same as in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, local companies increased investment in
technological development by 8.2 percent last year over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Medium-sized and large companies boosted investment in
technological development by 9.2 percent to 47.87 billion yuan,
and increased their investment in product development by 9.5
percent to 24.52 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local economists said that the growing role of local companies
in research and development funding indicates the effect of the
government's policy to stimulate investment.
</P>
<P>
They said that the government's input into the technological
renovation of State-owned enterprises has begun to push up the
companies' demand for investment in technology.
</P>
<P>
However, they pointed out that the per capita funding for
scientific and technological advancement in China is still low.
The funding for research and development (R&AMP;D) is yet to be
increased.
</P>
<P>
The NBS report shows that China's spending on R&AMP;D grew more
slowly last year than in the previous year, accounting for only 0.
69 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The report shows that spending on basic research saw a slower
growth rate, and spending on application research decreased last
year. Bloated organizations wasted a great part of the R&AMP;D money,
it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Threat From Pakistan: Indian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Indian Defense Minister George
Fernandes Thursday said he did not visualize any threat from
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters, "I don't feel there is any type of threat
(from Pakistan). If there is any problem, we are prepared....."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the two countries were on the brink of war,
particularly because both have nuclear weapons, he said he was not
worried about the two being nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
"But," he stressed, "we are not on the brink of war" and
"everything is in control." 
</P>
</TEXT>
