<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The number of ships arriving in Dubai during the first
six months of this year stood at 3,514 ships from neighboring
countries, the Arab economic daily Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Iran ranks the first with 2,764 ships arriving at Dubai,
followed by Somalia, India, Pakistan and Iraq with 518 ships
collectively and the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states with 232
ships.
</P>
<P>
The number of ships departing from Dubai amounted to 5,094
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Iran also ranks the first with 4,194 ships, followed by
Somalia, India, Pakistan and Iraq with 592 ships, and the United
Arab Emirates with 308 ships.
</P>
<P>
The volume of goods handled in the port hit 51,204,711
kilograms during the period, an increase of about 25 percent over
the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Imports volume of the Abu Dhabi Emirate stood
at 10.70 million dirhams (2.9 million U.S. dollars) during the
first six months of this year, up by 25 percent from the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, re-exports volume declined by 40 percent to 423
million dirhams (115.2 million dollars) during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Non-petroleum exports dropped by 4.2 percent to 340 million
dirhams (92.6 million dollars) as compared to 355 million dirhams
(96.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Remittances by Tunisian expatriates amounted to 892.4
million dinars (about 811.27 million dollars) last year against
845 million dinars (768.18 million dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Arab economic daily Alam Al Yom Thursday quoted a report by
the Tunisian Central Bank as saying that the increase in
remittances has helped cut down deficit in the current account
balance.
</P>
<P>
Remittances by Tunisians working abroad were ranked as
Tunisia's second biggest hard currency earner after tourism.
</P>
<P>
Tunisians working abroad are estimated at about 660,000 people,
7.4 percent of the country's 7.9 million population.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Gulf states are seeking to maintain their surplus
production estimated at over 4 million barrels per day in order to
ensure oil market stability and to meet the anticipated growth in
future demand for Gulf petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia alone is investing more than 1.5 billion dollars a
year to maintain its unexploited production capacity which is
estimated at some 3.5 million barrels a day, the Arab daily Al
Hayat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that total production capacity of sustained
petroleum in Saudi Arabia amounts to about 10.6 million barrels a
day, 2.7 million barrels a day in the United Arab Emirates and
about 2.6 million barrels a day in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia cut its oil production by about 1.3 million
barrels a day, UAE by about 380,000 barrels a day and 370,000
barrels a day in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the Gulf region will in the long run be the
principal source of petroleum supplies in view of its huge
petroleum reserves and giant oilfields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
