<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi High Court Orders Halt to Removing Slums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's High Court Thursday
extended its stay order issued Wednesday till August 17 directing
the government not to remove any more slums in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
A High Court Division Bench fixed the date of further hearing
of the writ petition challenging the eviction of slums.
</P>
<P>
The court passed the order Wednesday in response to the writ
petition filed by three non-governmental organizations and two
slum dwellers against the government and six other respondents.
</P>
<P>
The writ petition challenged the legality and authority of the
demolition of slums in the capital city and the eviction of
inhabitants without arranging alternative accommodation and
without any prior notice.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Mahmudul Islam, representing the government,
said Thursday that the government had taken a decision to
rehabilitate some of the slum people and the government's
rehabilitation program for the slum dwellers would be submitted
during the next hearing.
</P>
<P>
It is said that there are around 2 million slum dwellers in
Dhaka, which has a population of about 9 million.
</P>
<P>
A section of the slum dwellers under the patronage of some
godfathers were involved in drug and arms trafficking, and the
eviction drive, aimed at cutting crime and criminal activities,
would continue till the removal of the last slum from the capital,
according to police.
</P>
<P>
The government took the decision to clear all unauthorized
occupants from slums and level up illegal structures following the
killing of a police constable in the city last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
