<HEADLINE> Efforts Intensified to Rescue Hostages in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- British officials in the west
African region Thursday intensified their efforts to rescue six
European hostages including four British kidnapped Wednesday in
western Liberia, according to a report reaching here from
Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
British government has issued a warning in London against
non-essential travel to western Liberia and other trouble spots
in the region.
</P>
<P>
An armed gang kidnapped six European aid workers in a region
near the Liberia-Guinea border Wednesday, where Liberia's
government troops were fighting rebels.
</P>
<P>
Four of the captives are British, and the other two were
Norwegian and Italian, who are working with charity organizations
of Merlin and Doctors Without Borders.
</P>
<P>
The British citizens, including one female, were in the country
helping to rebuild hospitals, said the British Foreign Office
Wednesday in London.
</P>
<P>
The workers were seized Wednesday morning when armed men
entered their compound in Kolahun, Lofa County near the Sierra
Leone-Guinea border.
</P>
<P>
Merlin's director of operations Jules Pieters said in London
Thursday that there had been no contact with the hostage takers
but it was hoped that this could be established Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have not been able to get in touch with the kidnappers," he
said, adding "No demands have been made" from the kidnappers, the
British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) reported.
</P>
<P>
The area has been witnessing severe fighting between rebels
believed to be based in Guinea, and Liberian government troops.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor Wednesday declared a state
of emergency in Lofa County, where he said insurgents had
captured several towns overnight.
</P>
<P>
Taylor told journalists that rebel troops had broken across the
Guinean border Tuesday and taken Kolahun, one of Lofa County's
main towns, and a number of surrounding communities.
</P>
<P>
Government forces were being rushed to the front and Taylor
called on all "able-bodied men" to report for military service.
Government troops had closed Liberia's border with Guinea, said
the president. 
</P>
