<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Parliament Enacts Wiretapping Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) Thursday
enacted a set of bills that will allow investigators to wiretap
communications to fight organized crime, despite last-ditch
efforts by opposition parties to block their passage.
</P>
<P>
The House of Councillors passed the bills with 142 votes in
favor and 99 against. The ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP),
its coalition partner the Liberal Party (LP) and the No. 2
opposition New Komeito party backed the legislation.
</P>
<P>
The package includes a bill allowing law enforcement
authorities to wiretap private communications to investigate
crimes involving drugs, guns, murders committed by groups, and the
mass smuggling of people into Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has said the wiretapping legislation
would be a major weapon against organized crime, such as crimes
linked to the AUM Shinrikyo cult, as well as gun and drug
violations committed by underworld syndicates.
</P>
<P>
But critics argued the legislation would infringe on
constitutional provisions regarding the secrecy of communications
and protection of privacy.
</P>
<P>
The package, which cleared the House of Representatives (lower
house) in June, was railroaded through the upper house's Judicial
Affairs Committee Monday by the LDP, the LP and the New Komeito.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
