<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Somalis Killed in Demonstration Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- At least two Somalis were
killed and more than 10 others wounded during demonstrations
Wednesday against Ethiopians stationed in the border town of Bulo
Hawo.
</P>
<P>
Elders and businessmen who fled the town to neighboring Mandera
town across the Kenyan border said the people in the town have
been angered by the torture of three Somalis taken away by the
Ethiopians.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopians reportedly suspected the two as spies for the
Somali National Front (SNF) faction of General Omar Hajji Masalleh
allied with Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
During the violent demonstrations, the Ethiopian forces opened
fire at the sky in an attempt to disperse the crowd. But as some
of the demonstrators proceeded toward them, two were killed on the
spot. The Ethiopians have also rounded up more than 20 people
whose fate are still unknown.
</P>
<P>
Following the demonstrations, the Ethiopian forces imposed
curfew on the town blocking all entrances in and out of the town.
The Ethiopian soldiers erected roadblocks in several strategic
points and restricted all kinds of movements both traffic and
pedestrians alike. Residents of the town were told that the
curfew is effective from 5:00 p.m. local time everyday until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
The SNF faction has strongly condemned the killing and torture
of the Somalis by the Ethiopians in Bulo Hawo town. Its spokesman
Ibrahim Jama Howleh told reporters here Thursday in South
Mogadishu that the Ethiopian soldiers had behaved a lot worse
than any occupation force.
</P>
<P>
Howleh appealed to the Ethiopians to withdraw from the town and
other towns in Gedo region. The curfew, killing and the
demonstrations were also confirmed by the radio operators in other
towns and villages in Gedo region.
</P>
<P>
Despite the presence of Ethiopians in several regions in
southern Somalia, their military movements have been limited
following the alleged on-going underground discussions between the
faction of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and the Ethiopian government
brokered by Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
