<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Threaten Ethio-Djibouti Railway Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Railway between Ethiopian
capital Addis Ababa and Dire Dawa, the second largest city in the
country, has been disconnected temporarily due to threat of flood,
according a press release by the railway authorities available
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to stop the railway transport services was made to
spare passengers inconveniences on the way, the release said,
adding that the decision applies only to passengers and that
freight transport would continue as usual.
</P>
<P>
The railway, linking Addis Ababa and Dire Dawa, also goes to
Djibouti. The railway has become the only land channel for
Ethiopian import and export when the country began engaged in
border conflict with Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Dire Dawa is about 450 km east of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The serious flood in the Wolinchiti locality and the recent
heavy rains reportedly carried way minor dams.
</P>
<P>
Transport services between Addis Ababa and Dire Dawa will
resume immediately after the flood threat is thwarted through
practical measures taken by the railway, the release said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
