<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barmasai Admits Collusion in Golden League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Bernard Barmasai, one of
the four athletes to win the million dollar jackpot at the Golden
League, admitted Wednesday a collusion with compatriot Christopher
Koskei to keep him in the chase.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai, world 3,000 meter steeplechase record holder, said
his win in the Weltklasse Golden League athletics came from an
appeal to his friend, but not his running.
</P>
<P>
"His (Koskei's) last 100 meters are really good," said Barmasai.
"When he tried to pass I tried to talk to him. I said 'leave it
for me', and that's why he slowed down. He would have won today,
but because he is a friend and we have to live together...the
jackpot is for me and my friends."
</P>
<P>
Barmasai won the 3,000 meter steeplechase by just a stride
ahead of his countryman.
</P>
<P>
If Barmasai lost, American sprint-queen Marion Jones, Romanian
middle-distance specialist Gabriela Szabo and Denmark's 800-metre
world record holder Wilson Kipketer would suit to a three split of
the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
After Wednesday's Golden League meeting in Zurich, only two of
the seven stops remain, in Brussels and Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
