<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants New Multilateral Trade Negotiations to Start in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAULA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Thursday it
will stick by its decision that the new round of multilateral
trade negotiations under the auspices of the World Trade
Organization should start in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled preparatory meeting in Seattle this November
should be postponed to next year, Malaysian International Trade
and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said Thursday in Kuala Kangsar,
some 255 kilometers north from here, the Bernama news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and other developing countries are not ready for the
preparatory meeting and the "millennium round" of the multilateral
trade negotiations as they are still focusing on reviving their
economies and overcoming domestic problems, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Our stand is that there must be a new round (of negotiations)
but the announcement shouldn't be made in November in Seattle,"
she was quoted as saying after opening a school there.
</P>
<P>
She said Malaysia could only agree if the preparatory meeting,
which would determine the agendas for the negotiations, would be
held next year at a ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries need more time, at least one year, to
settle their domestic problems before shifting their attention on
other agendas to be discussed at the meeting, she said.
</P>
<P>
"As for Malaysia, we are busy with the issue of reviving our
economy and this multilateral issue must be kept aside first. We
prefer bilateral (negotiations) at this moment," she said.
</P>
<P>
While waiting for the new round, developing countries can
discuss their trade agendas in existing forum, including the G-77,
G-15, and ASEAN, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We could also use other fora for developing countries to
discuss issues of the (multilateral trade negotiations) agenda.
One year is not long," she said.
</P>
<P>
She said it is more appropriate for the new round of
negotiations, or millennium round, to begin in the year 2001
because the millennium would actually start from that year.
</P>
<P>
"They were wrong when they said the millennium starts from the
year 2000. So give us that one year, we agree (with the new round)
but fix it in 2001," she said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the date for the new round could only be made
after all the countries agreed to it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
