<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of Electric Railway Starts in SE China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a regional
electric railway started today in southeast China's Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Waiyang-Fuzhou railroad to stretch 191 km long west to east
in the province will be hooked with another electrified railway to
make up of a regional electric railway network, which is the first
of its kind in eastern China.
</P>
<P>
To be built at a cost of nearly one billion yuan (120 million
US dollars), the railway will be completed by the end of next year.
In addition to the track laying, some 348 km long electric wires
will be installed and four electricity-transformer stations will
be built.
</P>
<P>
The railroad is expected to alleviate the transportation strain
in the coastal province, which has a large amount of passenger and
cargo flow.
</P>
<P>
China plans to build 730 kilometers of electric railways this
year, according to an announcement of the Ministry of Railways
last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
