<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Promote Kosovo Peacekeeping Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) - Britain said Thursday that NATO's
commander in Kosovo, British Lieutenant-General Mike Jackson, is
to be moved up to full general next year.
</P>
<P>
A Defense Ministry spokesman said the veteran soldier will
become commander-in-chief of Land Command next March.
</P>
<P>
Born into a military family, Gen. Jackson, 55, joined the army
at the age of 19. He graduated from Birmingham University in 1967
and transferred to the Paras in 1970 after learning Russian in the
Intelligence Corps.
</P>
<P>
The general rose to command the First Battalion of the
Parachute Regiment between 1984 and 1986.
</P>
<P>
Jackson is expected to complete his tour as the commander of
peacekeeping force for Kosovo, known as KFOR, in Kosovo in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
