<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Children Addicted to TV: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The British spend around 15 years
of their waking lives staring at the television and addiction to
the small screen is growing all the time, according to a survey
published by The Times newspaper on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Millions of people are being damaged and billions of hours of
our lives wasted through intended and culpable media addiction,"
said the report, entitled Media Addiction.
</P>
<P>
"Children's educational development is undermined by media
addiction, even before they start school, and any serious attempt
to address educational standards must consider it," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"Media addiction, especially among children, has destructive
effects on basic aspects of life. It undermines speaking, thinking,
sleeping, emotions, activity, seeing concentration, reading, the
shaping of beliefs, growth of relationship and people's sense of
identity," it added.
</P>
<P>
The report warned instead of having a strong sense of their own
identity and personality, children are infatuated with stars such
as David Beckham and Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
It said addiction to TV may be one of the biggest problems of
the age, linked in turn to a poorly developed conscience, a
detached approach to violence and other ills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African Gas Pipeline Project to Be Completed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The West African Gas Pipeline
Project will be completed in 28 months' time with Benin, Ghana and
Togo receiving the first delivery of gas from Nigeria on January
1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
A Memorandum of Understanding on the project was signed
Wednesday in Cotonou, capital of Benin, between the West African
Gas Pipeline Project developer and the project implementation
committee, This Day newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Benin Energy Minister Felix Eson Danson said
that the memorandum was a significant event as it gave what he
called a new vista to the implementation of the project.
</P>
<P>
He also described the memorandum signing exercise as a
demonstration of the commitment of the participating governments
of Nigeria, Benin, Ghana and Togo to the success of the project.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture agreement was also signed by a commercial group
 consisting of Shell, Chevron, Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation, Ghana National Petroleum Corporation, Societe
Beninoise de Gaz, South Africa, and Societe Togolaise de Gaz,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The commercial group agreed to expedite the development of the
project and appointed Chevron Nigeria Limited as the project
manager.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture agreement is a follow-up to the decision
reached by the consortium in August last year in Lagos to launch a
private sector initiative to accelerate implementation of the
project.
</P>
<P>
The 960-km project which was first initiated by a World Bank
study on how best to utilize Nigeria's rich but flared gas
resources is designed to deliver Nigerian gas to domestic and
industrial consumers in Benin, Ghana and Togo.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is expected to deliver between 50 million and 160
million standard cubic feet of Nigerian gas daily to these
countries.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is expected to take 75 percent of the gas to feed its old
and new thermal plants at Tano, Takoradi and Tema while Benin and
Togo will utilize the gas for electricity generation.
</P>
<P>
The three countries, according to the World Bank, would be able
to save about 500 million U.S. dollars in energy cost over a
period of 20 years when gas replaces their expensive fuels and
hydro power currently used for power generation.
</P>
<P>
The benefits of the project include acting as a prototype for
the interconnection of the region, reduction of greenhouse gas
emissions by 100 million tons and availability of reliable, low
cost energy, according to a feasibility study on the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
