<HEADLINE> Israel Sees Threat of Iraqi Arms Growing: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Over the past few weeks,
Israel has thrust the Iraqi threat high up on its list of
diplomatic and security priorities, the local daily Haaretz
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In all their diplomatic meetings, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Foreign Minister David Levy reportedly voiced concern over
the Iraqi arms build up after the departure of UN
inspectors overseeing Iraq's non-conventional weapons program.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein recently intensified verbal
attacks on Israel, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In his July 17 Independence Day speech, Saddam called for
Israel's destruction and removal of Zionism from "Arab
Palestine."
</P>
<P>
He attacked those Arab leaders who are seeking peace with
Israel and expressed admiration for "the man calling himself the
new prime minister of the Zionist entity."
</P>
<P>
Barak has been calling Saddam Hussein's Iraq a serious threat
because of the Iraqi leader's drive to obtain chemical, biological
and nuclear weapons, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted intelligence sources as saying Iraq could
regain at least a certain degree of its biological and chemical
capability within nine months after the lifting of the
international inspection.
</P>
<P>
The sources also believe that the Iraqis are continuing to
make headway on gathering know-how, equipment, experts and
material for their nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
Israel's diplomatic efforts have been focused mainly on
returning the international inspectors to Iraq, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iraqi threat was discussed extensively during a
July visit to Washington by a senior intelligence official of
Israeli army, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, is also scheduled to visit Israel next week and the issue
of the Iraqi threat is expected to be raised in his meetings with
Barak and the heads of Israel's defense establishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
