<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Sets Int'l Directions for Next millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Thursday announced
its international directions for the next millennium which include
promoting a stable environment in East Asia, forging stronger
bonds with Northeast Asia as well as continuing to foster good
bilateral relations with other countries.
</P>
<P>
The outlines of Malaysia's course of action in the near future
were given by Foreign Minister Syed Hamid during a talk on
"Malaysia's International Direction in the International Arena in
the Next Millennium" at the National Institute of Public
Administration here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that obviously, Malaysia's international direction in
the next millennium will be influenced not only by external
developments but also internal factors.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia also faces manifold challenges such as globalization,
revolutions in the information and communications technology and
the diversity of issues and conflicting interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said Malaysia will nurture positive interstate
relations especially with its neighbors and countries of
particular importance.
</P>
<P>
In dealing with bilateral relations with neighbors, Malaysia
will continue to adopt win-win formulas and resolve all
differences peacefully through negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in a wider regional context, that is in the
ASEAN-plus-three (China, Japan and South Korea) context, Malaysia
will remain a firm advocate of the strategic and economic
importance of cooperation with China, Japan and the Republic of
Korea.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will also continue to be pro-active at the
multilateral level by participating in coalitions or caucuses to
promote interests and rights, especially of the developing
countries, Syed Hamid said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
