<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Court Papers Much Longer Than Before (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's court verdict papers,
which used to be three to five pages long during the past several
decades, are ballooning to 20 and 30 pages, as part of the country
's ongoing judicial reform.
</P>
<P>
The papers now record the full course of the trial and how the
evidence was presented and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
This reform is part of efforts to fully implement the principle
of "open trials," said Xiao Yang, president of the Supreme People'
s Court, in an interview with Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
"Openness of the reason for judgment is just as important as
opening trials to the public," he said, noting that the previously
monotonous and oversimplified court verdict papers were
insufficient to reflect the openness and equity of court verdicts.
</P>
<P>
Since he took the office of Supreme Court President in 1998,
Xiao has been pushing for open trials across the country.
</P>
<P>
In Chinese courts, judges used to announce that a judgment was
made based on a certain part of a certain article of a certain law,
without even citing the specific contents of the law. Few people
could understand how the judgment was made.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, Western court papers usually bore listeners to
death by containing a complete transcript of the entire trial.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese courts now are following their Western counterparts.
In May this year, the Supreme Court issued a manual titled "Model
Papers of Criminal Lawsuit," which requires judges to record all
the important evidence and arguments presented to the court, as
well as how they analyzed the material and reached their verdicts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Court Papers Much Longer Than Before (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Judges should convince both defendants and prosecutors or
plaintiffs why the verdicts are fair through their court papers,"
Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
A recent court paper on the first instance trial of tobacco
giant Chu Shijian in Yunnan Province was more than 30 pages, as
confirmed by Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
However, one judge said it could have been just three pages
before the reform.
</P>
<P>
According to Supreme People's Court judges, based on experience
in criminal trials, they are collecting court paper samples of
civil and economic cases and trying to formulate standards for
implementation across the country.
</P>
<P>
In fact, reform of court papers is just part of the judicial
reforms initiated by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
According to a five-year reform plan in the making, the Court
will push for further comprehensive reforms for trial methods,
mechanisms for verdict enforcement, internal structures, a people'
s jury system, and internal checks and balances.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts amount to the creation of a just, open,
efficient, and clean and honest judicial system that ensures fair
and independent trials, according to Xiao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
