<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Libraries Grows Rapidly in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China's library sector is
experiencing a rapid growth as more new libraries are opened while
service improved, according to a report in today's Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 2,600 public libraries of county-level
or higher, which have a total floor space of four million square
meters, compared with 1,732 libraries with a floor space of 650,
000 sq m around the year of 1980, the report quoted a researcher
with the China Society of Library Science as saying.
</P>
<P>
"That means in every 3.7 days a new public library is opened in
China," Wu Jianzhong said, describing the growth rate as "world-
leading".
</P>
<P>
Apart from some modern libraries built in the early 1990s, such
as the National Library in Beijing and the Shanghai Library, a
group of large-scale public libraries are under construction or
planned to be built in Shandong and Anhui provinces, and Shenyang,
Nanjing and Shenzhen cities.
</P>
<P>
The researcher added that more and more Chinese libraries
attach importance to improving service, such as extending the work
hours, even during weekends and holidays. The Shanghai Library has
become accessible all days a year.
</P>
<P>
Some new forms of libraries have been emerging, such as
libraries on the bus and the ship and in jails, in order to make
the libraries more accessible, Wu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Aims to Wipe out Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China aims to basically wipe out poverty by the end of
the century, according to a poverty-relief working conference held
recently in Lhasa, capital of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The number of poverty-stricken farmers and herdsmen in Tibet
has reportedly dropped from 870,000 in the late 1970s to a present
figure 147,000 thanks to a series of preferential policies granted
by China's central government.
</P>
<P>
Since the country adopted its reform and opening up policy in
1978, the central government has invested a total of 26 billion
yuan (3.13 billion US dollars) to help Tibet create projects to
improve the region's infrastructure facilities and mobilized other
localities to help the region with 105 projects.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Tibet has built 390 water conservancy
facilities to expand irrigated farmland by 30,700 hectares and
reclaim 19,300 hectares of low-yielding land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Enslaved At Least 170,000 Chinese Laborers in Building Fortress against Soviet Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- New evidence shows that the
Japanese used at least 170,000 Chinese laborers and make them toil
to build a fortress in northernmost China against a possible
attack by the Soviet Union during the World War II over half a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
According to an extensive, in-depth survey conducted by the
Heilongjiang Provincial Revolutionary Museum, the 110 by 50
kilometers Dongning Fortress was the largest of its kind in Asia,
concentrating a great number of bastions and armories.
</P>
<P>
"At least 170,000 Chinese laborers were enlisted and enslaved
in 11 years between 1934 and August of 1945, when the Japanese
troops were defeated and surrendered, to build the fortress in
Dongning County bordering Russia," said Cheng Penghan, head of the
research group.
</P>
<P>
He said the group has spent half a year studying historical
documents and carrying out field study and investigations. They
have discovered three burial grounds near the fortress, one of
which contained the remains of more than 3,000 bodies of Chinese
laborers.
</P>
<P>
Cheng went on to say that they also found a document by a
former Japanese officer which disclosed that many of the laborers
were held captive, and most of them worked to death or died of
hunger and illness, while others were secretly killed during the
construction of the fort.
</P>
<P>
According to recollections of Huang Shiyi and Zhao Jinbao, two
aged villagers of Laochengzigou, who were forced by the intruding
Japanese soldiers to transport corpses of Chinese laborers then,
they often moved two or three laborers' corpses by horse cart
daily and a dozen corpses a day at times, and they did the same
job again and again for the whole of three years.
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops intruded into northeast China in 1931 and
propped up the puppet country of Manchuria rulers there, which
received tens of thousands of Japanese immigrants.
</P>
<P>
However, the fortress failed to hold back the marching Soviet
army in 1945, when the Soviet Leader Joseph Stalin declared war
against Japan according to an agreement he had signed with United
States and British leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Warn of Ozone Depletion Over Qingha-Tibet Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Experts have warned that an hole
in the ozone layer will be formed over the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau
if prompt, effective measures are not taken to deal with the low
ozone distribution phenomenon occurring over the Plateau this
summer.
</P>
<P>
The ozone depletion phenomenon over the plateau has led to a
rising trend over recent years in the incidence of cataracts in
local people, mutations among animals and plants, and a
deterioration of the ecological environment in Tibet, according to
the experts.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has the highest incidence of cataracts in China.
</P>
<P>
Ozone modifies the strength of the ultraviolet radiation
reaching the Earth, and is essential to life on the planet.
</P>
<P>
International environment protection organizations have been
conducting a survey in Tibet to determine the amount of
destruction done to the ozone layer over the Plateau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
