<HEADLINE> Zambians Urged to Develop Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has urged
people owning undeveloped land to develop it, otherwise the land
would be repossessed.
</P>
<P>
Lands Minister Samuel Miyanda said that it was not government's
wish to repossess land, but it was just a way of encouraging
people to develop their land.
</P>
<P>
The minister said his ministry would not allow a situation
where people kept their land idle, Zambia Daily Mail newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda made this call when he officiated at a raffle draw of
winners of land in Lusaka wednesday, who entered the competition
at just ended 73rd Zambian agricultural and commercial show.
</P>
<P>
The prizes on offer by the government were seven plots in
Chinika Area in Lusaka Province.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda said the small holdings competition was restricted to
women as a way of addressing gender imbalance in land ownership.
</P>
<P>
"My ministry decided that the small holdings would be open for
competition to ladies only," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government had put up a deliberate policy
to allocate 10 percent of any land allocation to women in any area
in addition to other women allocation on merit.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry embarked on the draw competition as an
extension to their community service, adding that the winners of
the raffle would soon be invited to collect their title deeds.
</P>
<P>
The government would support a vegetable and flowering
processing and export project in Chinika Area, in which 200
Zambians are expected to be allocated, the minister said.
</P>
