<HEADLINE> Western Kenya Faces Maize Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Western Province in Kenya will
experience a shortfall of over 1.5 million 90-kg bags of maize
this year, the provincial Agricultural Director David Nyasani has
said.
</P>
<P>
Releasing his report on maize production Wednesday, Nyasani
said his province required six million bags of maize to cater for
the region's population and for sale to other areas suffering
food deficit, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that maize output had this year dropped and was
estimated at 4. 3 million bags after the long rains (March to
June) in the crop growing areas.
</P>
<P>
The director announced that during the short rain (September to
December) , the province was expected a small quantity of the crop
which will add up to a total production of about 4.5 million bags
for the long and short rains.
</P>
<P>
Nyasani attributed the shortfall in maize production to late
planting due to a shortage of maize seeds variety which farmers
in the province prefer and the delayed onset of the long rains.
</P>
<P>
Local media earlier reported that scarce rains during the long
rains recorded poor maize harvest in major maize growing areas in
Kenya and the country is facing a shortage of two million bags of
maize this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of July, the Kenyan government announced to cut its
tariff on maize import to 25 percent from 32.5 percent in a bid
to encourage cereal traders to import maize from outside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
