<HEADLINE> Downing of Aircraft Complicates Peace Process: Pak PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Thursday that the shooting down of an unarmed Pakistan
Navy aircraft by India would further complicate the already
strained ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"It was a cowardly act," Sharif said during a funeral service
held in Karachi for the 16 navy personnel killed Tuesday when the
aircraft was shot down by Indian jet fighters in Pakistan's
territory.
</P>
<P>
Attending the funeral service were also top civilian and
military officers.
</P>
<P>
Funeral prayers were held at the Mehran naval base where 16
coffins wrapped in Pakistani flags were lined up. Sharif and the
chiefs of the three services laid floral wreaths.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan Navy Atlantic aircraft was shot down Tuesday
morning by Indian air force aircraft. The Indian side claimed that
the Pakistani plane was shot down when it intruded into Indian air
space. However, Pakistan has categorically rejected the Indian
charge.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed that the navy plane was unarmed and
was on a routine training mission in Pakistan's air space. It
posed no threat to India which committed an act of "military
aggression," said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Indian act was a "grave violation" of international norms
and the relevant bilateral agreements, he said, adding that "it
will further complicate and cast a shadow over the bilateral peace
process." 
</P>
