<HEADLINE> Filipino Golfer Wins His First Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Filipino
golfer Gerald Rosales took his Southeast Asian Games gold medal,
puting Thailand and Philipines in Thursday's medal race.
</P>
<P>
With a final-round 69, Rosales ended at 15-under 273, winning
by six shots, and also helped the Philippines pull out a one-shot
victory over Thailand for the team title.
</P>
<P>
Thailand won the women's individual and team titles, helping
their nation stay ahead in the games' overall gold medals race.
</P>
<P>
After early events Thursday, Thailand had 46 golds to 42 for
Malaysia and 33 for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines edged Thailand 846-847 for the golf team gold,
with Malaysia taking the bronze with 855.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Gulyanamitta Russamee shot a one-over 73 and won the
women's gold by one shot despite a bogey on the final hole. She
finished at 2-under 214 for 54 holes, and teammate Sattayabanphot
Onnarin won the silver with 215 after a final-round 72.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Gulyanamitta Jaruwan was next at 216, but under
rules limiting a country to two gold medals in one event, Malaysia
's Lim Ai Lian took the bronze with 220.
</P>
<P>
Thailand won the team gold with 428. Malaysia beat Indonesia
for the silver in a sudden-death playoff after each finished at
443.
</P>
<P>
Thais and Filipinos also were winners at shooting Thursday.
Thailand beat the Philippines in the men's skeet team event. In
the trap team event, the Philippines won with 322 to 317 for
Singapore and 314 for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's Dominic Lim emerged as the highest scoring tenpin
bowler of the games, averaging 219 as he amassed 5,261 pins for
the singles, doubles, trios and five-man events. Thailand's
Kritchawat Jumpakhao won the all-events silver medal , and
Malaysia's Ricky Chen took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
In the five-man competition, Chen's Malaysian team won the gold
with 6,356 to 6,143 for Singapore and 6,068 for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In bowling on the lawn, Malaysia won the four-man gold by
beating silver medalist Brunei 24-13, and Singapore took the
bronze with a 21-20 victory over Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia won the 800-meter, 22-man race in traditional boats,
nearly six seconds ahead of silver medalist Myanmar. Myanmar edged
Indonesia by .56 second in the 22-woman boats. In all, Indonesia
won five of the games' eight boat races and Myanmar won three.
</P>
</TEXT>
