<HEADLINE> Chinese Mother Gives Birth to Quadruplets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese woman soldier in east
China's Jiangsu Province yesterday successfully gave birth to four
babies in a military hospital.
</P>
<P>
Ni Ying, 28 years old, who is also a doctor in the hospital's
contagious diseases department, gave birth to the first of the
quadruplets, weighing 3.3 pounds, at 6:44 yesterday morning. The
second baby, weighing 3.4 pounds, was born eight minutes later,
and the last two were born one hour later, each weighing 3.08
pounds.
</P>
<P>
Ni's delivery was five weeks ahead of the expected date, but
the four babies, all girls, are in good condition, and were soon
sent to a children's hospital nearby to receive special care.
</P>
<P>
According to Ni's doctor, it is unusual that she gave birth to
quadruplets, because she has neither a family history of multiple
births, nor did she take any drug to accelerate ovulation, which
are the two common circumstances resulting in multiple births.
</P>
<P>
A family planing official from the provincial government said
the four babies will receive government aid including free
educations and free home-care services.  
</P>
