<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sees Slowing Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 12 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's resident
population was estimated to have been 3,808,700 at June 30, 1999,
NZ's Deputy Government Statistician Dianne Macaskill said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Macaskill said that this represents an
increase of 17,800 or 0.5 percent over the figure a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"This growth rate is about two-fifths of the 1.3 percent
average annual growth rate of the previous five years," she said.
</P>
<P>
A turnaround in the external migration balance has been the
main factor in the slower growth. Permanent and long-term
departures exceeded arrivals by 11,400 during the year to June
30, 1999, compared with a small migration gain of 500 in the
previous year. Over the same period, natural increase (excess of
births over deaths) dropped slightly from 29,400 to 29,100,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The number of women compared to the number of men in the New
Zealand population continues to slowly increase. As at June 30,
1999, there were 103 women per 100 men, Macaskill said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
