<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Reaches 63.5% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's inflation has
surpassed all expectations to hit an all time high of 63.5 percent
in July, casting doubt on the efforts to meet the International
Monetary Fund's target of 30 percent by year end, the weekly
Business reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office Wednesday said the 8.3
percentage points increase from the June inflation figure of 55.2
percent came largely as a result of a 29.8 percentage points
increase in food prices with non-food prices having gone up by
33.8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
"The increase was mainly assisted by the recent increases in
the price of maize meal, beef, post and telecommunications service
tariffs and drink. On the other hand, the purchasing power
continues to decline, the value of the Zimbabwean dollar is now
equivalent to 9.7 cents in 1990," said the Central Statistical
Office in a report.
</P>
<P>
The government now faces an unenviable task of reducing
inflation, which will be heavily dependent on combination of
strict monetary and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the rate could reach its peak this month before
starting to decline in the last quarter of the year. The market
projects the August rate to reach 65 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
