<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Pays Tribute to "Rhino Man" in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) Thursday extended its condolences to the family
members of Michael Werikhe, known as "Rhino Man" in Mombasa, a
seaport city in southeastern Kenya, after learning of his tragic
death.
</P>
<P>
"It is the lives and actions of ordinary citizens that have
awakened the consciences of many of us to the numerous threats
posed to our environment",
</P>
<P>
said Klaus Toepfer, UNEP's Executive Director.
</P>
<P>
He added that "Michael will long be remembered for the positive
action he took to save species that could not protect itself from
man's destruction. We can only hope that there will be others to
continue his efforts."
</P>
<P>
Werikhe, popularly known as "Rhino man", was a renowned
conservationist who championed the cause of the endangered
rhinoceros.
</P>
<P>
He raised close to one million U.S. dollars for rhino
conservation in sponsored walks during 1982, 1985 and 1988,
covering nearly 5,000 kilometers in Kenya and several European
countries.
</P>
<P>
During his 1982 walk, Werikhe made a 479-kilometer trip to
publicize the killing of the black rhino, an animal he had never
seen. In 1985, he walked across Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda,
enlisting the assistance of his fellow Africans in saving the
rhino.
</P>
<P>
In recognition of his efforts, Werikhe was awarded UNEP's
Global 500 Award in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Michael once said: "the rhino is a living symbol of our
environment. It is a big animal, easy to watch. If something is
happening to this big animal, just imagine the problems of small
animals and our total environment."
</P>
<P>
According to the Kenya Wildlife Service, thanks to proper
protection measures, the number of black rhino in Kenya has
increased to 470 at present from 280 in 1984.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Installs Condom Automats on Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Following Shanghai and Guangzhou,
the Chinese capital has finally decided to place condom vending
machines on the streets for married couples' convenience.
</P>
<P>
The first two were installed Wednesday in the Haidian District,
Beijing's university area, for around-the-clock service. The pink
colored machine dispenses one condom for the price of a one-yuan
coin.
</P>
<P>
Seven coins had been collected by this morning, and observers
guess they were inserted by customers at night when there were few
people nearby.
</P>
<P>
"The machines will be welcomed by those who are shy about
buying condoms at shops, and it will help strengthen birth control
work," said Sun Linlin, a family planning official.
</P>
<P>
China, the world's most populous country, has ordered that an
urban married couple should give birth to just one child.
</P>
<P>
For a long period of time, the Chinese government provided 150
free condoms a year to one couple. But many Chinese now prefer to
buy condoms at shops, especially high-quality imported ones,
though the price of an imported condom is dozens of yuan.
</P>
<P>
Sun also suggested that there is a more open attitude towards
sex among Chinese youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The new machines and condoms were provided by a United Nations
fund, according to Sun, and a total of 70 machines soon will be on
the streets of Beijing and Shanghai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
