<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM's Coming Visit to China to Strengthen Bilateral Ties: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad will visit China from August 18 to 20, not only
to further enhance diplomatic relations but also result in more
joint-venture projects, Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's visit at the invitation of his Chinese counterpart
Premier Zhu Rongji is in conjunction with the 25th anniversary of
the establishment of diplomatic relations between Malaysia and
China.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is scheduled to call on President Jiang Zemin and hold
an official meeting with Zhu to discuss bilateral issues
especially on trade and investment, Syed Hamid told reporters
after delivering a lecture on "Malaysia's Direction In The
International Arena in The New Millennium" at the National
Institute of Public Administration here.
</P>
<P>
He said that among the joint ventures to be discussed was the
setting up of the Proton (Malaysia's national car manufacturer)
plant in one of the provinces of China.
</P>
<P>
China on the other hand is keen to set up a pulp and paper
factory in Sabah, East Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, total trade between China and
Malaysia last year stood at 4.264 billion U.S. dollars, a 20-fold
increase over that in early years of the establishment of
bilateral diplomatic relations. In the first half of this year,
total trade between the two countries reached 2.2958 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mutual investment has also been on an upswing in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
