<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Silk Industry Fighting Hard To Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Silk from the Chinese city of
Hangzhou is known worldwide but the silk industry in Zhejiang
Province, where the city is located, is struggling to get out of a
mess.
</P>
<P>
Because of outdated designs and stagnant domestic sales, China'
s silk industry headed for a fall in 1994 and went on to
accumulate losses of 320 million in 1995 in Zhejiang alone. But,
it took a turn for the better in the first half of this year, when
the province's silk industry had output worth 3.5 billion yuan and
a sales-to-output ratio of 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
Still, many insiders are pessimistic about the industry's
future and point to various difficulties both at home and abroad.
They say that some 60 to 70 percent of China's silk is destined
for overseas market with much of it going to Southeast Asia,
Europe, and America, where changing fashions and financial
difficulties have meant problems for the market.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show China's silk exports fell 15 percent to 2.5
billion U.S. dollars worth last year. Zhejiang's export fared a
bit better than average, increasing by 5.3 percent, to 1.28
billion dollars. But major silk producing areas of the eastern
Yangtze River Valley were affected this year by major flooding
that began in June. This year's floods caused 100 million yuan in
losses for Zhejiang's silk industry.
</P>
<P>
Analysts are calling for more flexible operations so that the
industry can adjust more readily to market fluctuations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
