<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   SAF to Carry Out Doping Tests on Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian Federation (
SAF) will test athletes for banned substances in its forthcoming
Games to be held from September 25 to October 4, The Rising Nepal
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President of the SAFG executive medical committee and chief
physician of the National Sports Council Dr. Ajay Rana said that
the doping program would be a new chapter in Nepal's hosting of
the regional meets.
</P>
<P>
Rana added that the tests are not going to done solely in Nepal.
Urine samples taken from the participating athletes during the
Games will be dispatched to Malaysia and the results will be faxed
back to Nepal as soon as the procedure ends in the laboratory,
said Dr. Rana.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Federation Games medical meeting on August 29
will decide on the dope control program, protocol and procedures,
said Rana.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that SAF Games is screening athletes
for banned drugs. The first SAF Games dope screening was done in
Pakistan, but it was discontinued in other games held in other
South Asian cities.
</P>
<P>
There will be a main medical center at the National Dasharath
Stadium in Nepal, well equipped and with all the medical apparatus,
while the doping center will be established within the National
Sports Council's sporting complex, said Rana.
</P>
<P>
He said the main center will be run around the clock with all
the necessary equipment, such as X-ray machines, pathology and
physiotherapy facilities. if needed, the center will be capable of
carrying out minor operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
