<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Name Layden General Manager, Sign Coach Van Gundy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The New York Knicks
successfully lured Scott Layden from the Utah Jazz and finally
signed coach Jeff Van Gundy to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
After 18 years in the Jazz organization, Layden left to become
the executive vice president and general manager of the Knicks
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This was an opportunity that was too good to pass up," Layden
said at an afternoon news conference. "It was a tough decision for
me to leave Utah, but I feel very fortunate to be given this
opportunity. Certainly, the New York Knicks are one of the premier
franchises."
</P>
<P>
Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts reached back to
his Utah roots to court Layden, who spent the last three years as
the Jazz's vice president of basketball operations. Utah released
Layden from his contract on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I had a chance to hire a guy who is clearly recognized as one
of the premier basketball executives in the NBA and I am delighted
he is joining us," Checketts said.
</P>
<P>
Checketts and Layden became close in Utah, where Checketts
served as club president for six years during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Layden was being paid roughly 400,000 U.S. dollars a year with
the Jazz, but reportedly received a four-year deal worth 6 million
U.S. dollars from the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
It was believed Ed Tapscott, the Knicks' vice president of
player personnel, would be promoted to the position of general
manager full time. He assumed the duties when Ernie Grunfeld was
demoted in April.
</P>
<P>
An unlikely run to the NBA Finals put Van Gundy back into the
good graces of Checketts and Cablevision executives after a
disappointing regular season.
</P>
<P>
Although terms were not disclosed, Van Gundy reportedly was
rewarded with a two-year extension through 2003 worth between 8
and 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Jeff is going to be with us a long time," Checketts said. "He
has achieved a lot with us and he's a great coach. We had quite a
run in the playoffs and what has impressed me the most is the way
he has communicated with the player."
</P>
<P>
Next year, Van Gundy is scheduled to earn $2 million, and with
the Knicks advancing to the NBA Finals in June, a $3.5 million
extension for the 2000-01 season automatically kicked in.
</P>
<P>
Layden is the son of former Jazz coach Frank Layden and has
worked in the Utah organization for the last 18 years. He joined
the Jazz in 1981 as an assistant coach and quickly moved up the
management ladder, first as head scout, then as director of player
personnel in 1988-89 and director of basketball operations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Van Gundy, 37, was the subject of constant rumors throughout a
disappointing regular season. The media had Van Gundy fired
numerous times during the lockout-shortened campaign, but he
remained on and barely guided the Knicks into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Van Gundy has a career record of 120-97 in three-plus seasons
with the Knicks. He took over the team in 1996 and guided the
Knicks into the Finals last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
