<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Jobless Drops to Nine Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Australia's unemployment rate
hit a nine year low of 7.0 percent in July as the job market
continued to show further signs of improvement, Australian Bureau
of Statistics said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate is now at its lowest level, seasonally
adjusted, since July 1990, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's figures showed that total employment rose by
17,800 in July from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
It followed strong job gains in June, suggesting Australia's
recent economic growth may finally be kicking into the jobs
market.
</P>
<P>
Australian Employment Minister Peter Reith said in a statement
that the figures showed the strong performance of the labor market
under this government.
</P>
<P>
"Needless to say these are only one month's figures and more
work needs to be done to consolidate the gains made to date and
further strengthen employment growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also found the number in the country's full-time
employment increased by 7,200 in July to 6.49 million from a year
earlier while part-time workers rose by 10,600 to 2.29 million.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment fell by 18,500 in July to 661,100 and youth
unemployment dropped from 23.0 percent to 21.4 percent in July,
seasonally adjusted.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate fell in all of the country's states except
Victoria, and was steady in Western Australia state, the bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
The data, along with improved gold prices, spurred the
Australian dollar nearly half a U.S. cent higher in the country's
exchange market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
