<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's AXA Opens Insurance Company in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 12 (Xinhua) -- France's AXA opened a joint
life insurance company, AXA-Minmetals Life, in Shanghai on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was started by AXA and China Minmetals Group, one of China's
largest foreign trade enterprises, with assets worth 2.3 billion U.
S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
AXA's chairman Claude Bebear said at an opening ceremony that
China's insurance market is undergoing many reforms and provides
huge development potential and that Shanghai has a favorable
investment environment. According to an AXA market survey,
Shanghai's life insurance business accounted for a fourth of the
country's total in 1998 and was worth more than 7 billion yuan.
This was 80 times the amount in 1995 and the business is expected
to grow by more than 30 percent annually for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
As China's housing, medicare, and pension reforms grow, people
will have to carry a much greater financial burden themselves and
this means a big insurance market, according to Joseph Sin, the
chairman of the board of the new company.
</P>
<P>
AXA-Minmetals is the 10th foreign-funded insurance company to
open in Shanghai. AXA itself was founded in 1816 and ranks 15th in
the Fortune 500 with total assets worth 655 billion U.S. dollars
and profits of 1.7 billion dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
