<HEADLINE> New Giant Panda Cub Born in Chengdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A Giant Panda cub was born
Sunday at the Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding Research Center in
China's Sichuan Province, according to a report reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
Both the cub, which weighed 170 grams at birth, and its mother
are said to be in good condition. It is given the name "qiu qiu" (
'autumn' in Chinese) because it was born on the first day of the
Autumn season.
</P>
<P>
The 30-hectare center in the northern suburbs of Chengdu has
been developing breeding technology since it used frozen semen for
artificial insemination in 1980. China used artificial
insemination to breed the first Giant Panda cub in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Fewer than 10 percent of the center's males and 24 percent of
its females are able to mate by themselves and, of the ll giant
panda births, 80 percent have been produced by artificial
insemination. Giant pandas only have one or two cubs each time.
</P>
<P>
There are only about 1,000 pandas in Sichuan, Gansu, and
Shaanxi provinces and 80 percent are in Sichuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
