<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White People Urged to Promote National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- President of the Commercial
Farmers' Union of Zimbabwe, Tim Henwood, Wednesday said whites
here should join the rest people of the country in promoting
national unity and development, the daily Herald reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview after he laid a wreath at the Tomb of the
Unknown Soldier at the National Heroes Acre in Harare, the white
farmer challenged the white community in the country to forget the
colonial past and join others in celebrating national events.
</P>
<P>
"I was here at the celebration of the Heroes Day last year and
it has become a custom of me. If we are to build the nation, we
have to build it together," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We must have gone past the stage where people do not
trust each other."
</P>
<P>
"We should always encourage each other to participate in
national events because this is our country and we are responsible
for developing it," said Henwood.
</P>
<P>
Asked why the majority of the whites in Zimbabwe had remained
reluctant to participate in national celebrations, Henwood said
whatever differences might have occurred, they should be a thing
of the past.
</P>
<P>
He said for the country to enjoy meaningful development, every
citizen should participate and go along with others.
</P>
<P>
"Together we make the nation and together we should develop our
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
August 11 was Zimbabwe's Heroes Day when thousands of
Zimbabwean people thronged the National Heroes Acre in Harare to
pay respects to the fallen heroes of the liberation struggle that
brought about the country's independence in 1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
