<HEADLINE> "Image Problem" Hampers Bangladesh's Shrimp Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The "image problem" is hampering
Bangladesh's shrimp exports though the country now has very high
quality shrimp processing plants producing best categories of
shrimps for exports, The Independent daily newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh fetched a total of 274 million U.S. dollars during
the 1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30 from exporting shrimps,
which experts said was 20 percent less than the standard
international market prices.
</P>
<P>
Market researchers, exporters and international consultants
said the country's shrimp industry was losing huge revenue for no
substantive reasons other than the country's rating abroad as a
least developed country, and the "image problem" had become the
main obstacle to Bangladeshi shrimp exports.
</P>
<P>
The competitive strength of the country's shrimp exporters
caused a loss of 67 million dollars as importers offered prices
lower than those offered for imports from other sources, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh also sustained a loss of 23 million dollars during
the last fiscal year due to a sudden slide in the shrimp prices in
the international market.
</P>
<P>
The country's shrimp export volume increased by 3,000 tons to
28,000 tons in fiscal 1998-99, but its earning is 23 million
dollars less than that of the previous fiscal year, which is 297
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The shrimp industry of Bangladesh has already overcome its
structural weakness, and the United States and the European Union
have recognized this development and now rated Bangladesh's shrimp
industry as one of the best equipped with standard hygienic and
health measures, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
