<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spectacular Waterfall On Yellow River Possibly to Dry Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The most famous waterfall on the
Yellow River is possible to disappear as a result of reduced water
flow, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey they had conducted on June 28 this year,
the Hukou Waterfall, in northwestern Shanxi province, had only 75
cubic meters of water per second going over it during this year's
flood season in sharp contrast to the 300 cubic meters per second
of previous years, affecting the charm of the scenic spot.
</P>
<P>
The waterfall is in a narrow, precipitous gorge and is known
for the rapid speed of the water and as the thunderous sound. It
attracts millions of tourists every year as well as adventurers
who have attempted, for example, to jump a motorcycle over it.
</P>
<P>
Scientists noted that water levels of the Yellow River have
continued to decline over recent years because of climate changes
and other reasons. Some sections of the river are dry for several
months every year, causing anxiety among people living along the
lower reaches.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River was known as the cradle of Chinese
civilization and for its extreme floods that took thousands of
lives, but scientists have warned that the river could itself
become seasonal if the environmental deterioration continues and
splendors like Hukou Waterfall could eventually become just a
distant memory in the not too distant future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Falls in First Half of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
fell to 6,301.3 billion yen (53 billion U.S. dollars) in the first
half of 1999, down 14.9 percent from a year earlier, the Finance
Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus -- the broadest measure of trade in
goods and services -- decreased as the stronger yen reduced the
competitiveness of exports, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the payments surplus was the first in five half-
year terms, before adjustment for seasonal factors.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, the surplus in goods and services
trade stood at 4,072.1 billion yen (34.3 billion U.S. dollars),
down 9.0 percent, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade surplus dropped 7.5 percent from a year
earlier to 7,016.2 billion yen (59.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Exports fell 9.2 percent to 22,187.2 billion yen (186.8 billion
U.S. dollars) while imports decreased 10.0 percent to 15,171.0
billion yen (127.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The current account balance is the difference between a country
's income from foreign sources and foreign obligations payable,
excluding net capital investment.
</P>
<P>
The yen averaged 118.81 to the dollar in the first half of this
year, compared with 132.03 in the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
