<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lanka's Business Community to Mediate with Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Business Forum
leader will meet the Tamil rebels in October with a set of
proposals agreed on by the two main parties to resolve the ethnic
conflicts, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Business Forum Lalith Kotelawala will seek to
persuade Tamil rebels of Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
back to the negotiating table, the official Daily News said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling People's Alliance government and the main opposition
United National Party (UNP) met in Colombo on Wednesday in a
meeting organized by the Business Forum chaired by Lalith
Kotelawala.
</P>
<P>
They will try their best to iron out existing differences by
September 30, a deadline agreed on by the two parties who will
meet in the next round of meeting on September 1, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Justice and Constitutional Affairs G.L. Peiris, who
headed the government delegation, described Wednesday's meeting as
a major breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Peiris said, "a set of proposals with a consensus of the
government and the main opposition would pressurize the LTTE to
divert itself for a political solution."
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been plagued by a 16-year-old war fought between
security forces and LTTE rebels who demand a homeland for minority
Tamils in the north and east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The government, which is committed to achieving a political
solution to the ethnic conflict, has come up with a devolution
package.
</P>
<P>
However, it requires a two third majority for passage in
Parliament which can be obtained only with the support of the UNP.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
