<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Premiers End Meeting With Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian provincial premiers and
territorial leaders ended their three-day meeting in Quebec City
on Wednesday,reaching consensus on tax cuts and investments in
infrastructure and shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
The 10 premiers and three territorial leaders agreed to urge
Ottawa to cut tax while investing in national highways and
shipyards.
</P>
<P>
Unlike three days ago, when the premiers were divided on what
the annual meeting should focus, the provincial and territorial
leaders were "excited" at the end of the meeting in a unanimous "
call for cash within existing budgets."
</P>
<P>
Canadian media said, however, that the leaders fell short of
specifying any of their requirements for money from the federal
budgets, as they did not want to "determine a minimum or maximum."
</P>
<P>
The ball is now in the court of Ottawa, and the media quoted
Alberta Premier Ralph Klein as saying that it will be hard for
Prime Minister Jean Chretien to ignore the results of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile in Ottawa, Finance Minister Paul Martin refused to
comment on budget specifics "this early," but believed that the
provincial and territorial leaders "confirm their support for the
approach" of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
"As long as premiers recognize that governments can't be all
things to all people, and that they have to make choices, I think
what essentially we are seeing is a confirmation of that approach,
" the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the premiers were actually discussing
ways to better share the 10 billion or more Canadian dollars (
about 6.7 billion U.S. dollars) in the federal budget surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt to Rely Less on Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
shift from foreign to domestic borrowings beginning next year in
an effort to arrest the continued decline of domestic interest
rates, the Philippine Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu as saying
Wednesday that the government will increase the ratio of its
domestic borrowings to total loans from only 30 percent this year
to 70 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Since interest rates are on a down-turn and there is no longer
any danger of crowding out domestic borrowers, the government
could go to domestic banks to borrow part of its budgetary
requirements, Espiritu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that once the government starts borrowing from
domestic sources, interest rates are expected to go up and ease
the attacks on the peso. At present, the peso is down to 39.165
pesos to the dollar as the Philippine Central Bank introduced a
cap on its borrowing to encourage banks to be more aggressive in
lending to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Sworn in Again As Venezuelan President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez,
who symbolically resigned last week, on Wednesday was sworn in as
president before the National Constitutional Assembly (NCA).
</P>
<P>
Chavez, elected in the December presidential elections,
testified as president for the first time on February 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, Chavez offered his resignation to the NCA and
called on the NCA to rewrite the country's present constitution,
which has been in effect since 1961. But his resignation was
rejected by the NCA, controlled by Chavez's supporters.
</P>
<P>
Among his proposals for a new constitution, Chavez called on
the NCA to extend the presidential term from five years to six
years and to allow all incumbents to be re-elected.
</P>
<P>
But Chavez's bid to rewrite the 1961 national charter was
strongly opposed by the Supreme Court and Congress, both
controlled by opposition parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
