<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Real Depreciates Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose to a
five-month high against the Brazilian real on Wednesday, as a
result of unstable foreign markets and Brazil's domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency, on the rise for the last two weeks, rose on
Wednesday by 0.54 percent from Tuesday's close, and reached at mid-
session in the free market a rate of 1.875 reals (buying) and 1.
878 reals (selling).
</P>
<P>
This price was the highest it had come to since March 12 when
it stood at 1.91 reals (buying), and 1.92 reals (selling).
</P>
<P>
A rise in the dollar was also seen on the parallel market in
Sao Paulo, where the dollar was purchased at 1.88 reals, and sold
at 1.91 reals, while in the tourist sector it registered at 1.84
reals (buying) and 1.91 reals (selling).
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Brazil's exchange market was under strong
buying pressure as a result of the nervousness of investors about
a possible interest increase and a lack of confidence in domestic
politics.
</P>
<P>
According to director of Renova Corredora company Miriam
Tavares, the market was nervous at rumors of the possible quit of
Finance Minister Pedro Milan.
</P>
<P>
Director of International Affairs of the Central Bank, Daniel
Gleizer, expected that the exchange market would calm down in the
next few days, when banks reduce their purchasing of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
