<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Not to Blame for Trade Disputes With Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- In the matter of trade disputes,
it takes two to tango, said Brazilian Foreign Minister Luiz Felipe
Lampreia, when refuting charges that Brazil is to blame for the
ongoing trade tension with neighboring Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia said Wednesday that while the devaluation of the
Brazilian currency, the real, did play a role, it was not the only
cause for Brazil's rapid rising exports of footwear, textiles,
household appliances and other goods to the Argentine market.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's economic recession, which started last September,
and the lack of modernization of its industrial sectors, played an
important part in the country's declining competitiveness against
Brazilian products, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some sectors of the Argentine economy did not go
all out to cater to the domestic demand, leaving a gap for foreign
goods to fill, said Lampreia.
</P>
<P>
Both Brazil and Argentina are members of the four-nation
Southern Cone Common Market (Mercosur). The bloc has been facing
its most serious row since its two biggest members went bitter
over trade because of the real's devaluation in January.
</P>
<P>
Lampreia said Brazil would not leave Mercosur, which is
valuable to the country, nor would it accept restrictive measures
against the principle of free trade.
</P>
<P>
He said Brazil will file a complaint with the World Trade
Organization against an Argentine trade restriction curbing its
textile exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Institute Sees Asian Economy on Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Signs of economic recovery have
appeared, by and large, in the Asian countries which were hit by
financial crisis in the past few years, the German Institute for
Economic Research said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is likely to regain a fairly strong economic growth
this year while Thailand will see a very weak growth and Malaysia
may expect a rebound, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that the Indonesian economy will downslide again,
only at a slower speed than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that the recovery of the Asian economy is
closely related to the financial restructuring, which is designed
to establish internationally competitive financial systems in
those countries.
</P>
<P>
The report believed that the restructuring of commercial banks
and the reform of the credit-releasing practices can play a major
role in boosting the economy.
</P>
<P>
These measures can help set up effective business supervision
mechanisms and achieve overall economic recovery in this region,
said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historic Sites Found in Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered some 39 historic sites in northeast China's Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
These sites were found at a dozen expressway and railway
construction areas, and the oldest dates back to the Bronze Age (
16th-11th centuries B.C.). The others are of the Han Dynasty (206-
24 B.C.), Liao Dynasty (916-1125), Jin Dynasty (1115-1234), Yuan
Dynasty (1271-1368), Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) and Qing Dynasty (
1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Among the relics are two special tombs of ancient Koreans who
lived along with a variety of other ethnic groups in northeastern
China.
</P>
<P>
A local archeologist said the discovery of these sites will
provide valuable material for the study on the ancient politics,
ethnic groups, and ethnic cultures of the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
