<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Exchange Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's net foreign exchange
reserves increased slightly, by 99.7 million U.S. dollars to
16.214 billion dollars, in the week ending on August 6, from
16.115 billion dollars the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly due to the disbursement of 107.1
million dollars in loans from Japan, the central bank said in a
weekly report, quoted by The Jakarta Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Net foreign exchange reserves were now well above the
International Monetary Fund-adjusted target of 14.3 billion
dollars, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said its gross foreign exchange reserves,
which are net foreign exchange reserves plus outstanding foreign
exchange contracts, also increased during the week by 95.6 million
dollars to 26.68 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
