<HEADLINE> Colombian President Promises to Combat Common Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana said on Wednesday that his government will seek
security and peace for all Colombians.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana made the promise when he announced that an Academic
Mission will be set up to analyze the causes of crime and 100
Centers of Immediate Attention (CIA) will be put into action to
control urban insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said that security is a fundamental element for the
restoration of investor confidence and an essential factor for the
creation of employment.
</P>
<P>
"The main condition for the progress of a country is that its
citizens have confidence in the state by way of its security
organizations. It guarantees everyone has the sacred right to live
without anxiety, to move without fear and to work without danger,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, more than 55 percent of
Colombians are concentrated in 59 municipalities, which account
for 60 percent of homicides.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, there has been a new call to the local mayors
of the country to restrict the carrying of arms during weekends so
as to reduce violence and create a peaceful environment for
residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
