<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Athletes Still in Hunt for Golden League Jackpot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unbeaten in track events since 1997, American world champion
sprinter Jones held off compatriot Inger Miller at the finish to
win in 22.10 seconds, her 21st consecutive 200 meter win.
</P>
<P>
In the 3,000m steeplechase, world record holder Barmasai had
looked poised to register another easy victory as he bolted into
an early lead.
</P>
<P>
But the Kenyan instead was forced to fend off a late charge
from Christopher Koskei, crossing in 8:05.16 just a stride ahead
of his compatriot.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer, the 800m world record holder, had to fight off a
challenge from South Africa's Hezekiel Sepeng, crossing a half
second clear of the South African in 1:43.01.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Gabriela Szabo, the only other athlete in the hunt
for the jackpot, produced the most comfortable victory, crossing
first in the women's 3,000m in 8:25.03.
</P>
<P>
All four can collect a share of the jackpot if they can win in
Brussels and Berlin and sweep their seven Golden League events.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Violeta Szekely became the first woman to run under
four minutes this season in the women's 1,500m.
</P>
<P>
Pushed by Anita Weyermann, who was trying to become the first
Swiss to win in Zurich since 1993, Szekely clocked 3:59.31
</P>
<P>
American world record holder Maurice Greene was an easy winner
of the men's 100m ahead of Obadele Thompson, going under 10
seconds for the fifth time this season in 9.99. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
