<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,100-Year Old Fresco Tomb Found in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
excavated an ancient tomb with unusual wall frescoes in Horinger
County, in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The brick tomb, dating back to the Tang Dynasty (618-907), has
an arched roof about three meters wide and four meters high,
according to Chen Yongzhi, a local archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
The skeleton of the tomb occupant, whose sex is still
undetermined, was found on a raised platform. The chamber walls
are decorated with colored frescoes featuring scenes of everyday
life, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
One scene shows a typical living room of Tang times, with a
door, lattice windows and pillars. Two plump maids in long gowns
are poised beside the door.
</P>
<P>
Another scene is of two male servants in colorful clothes and
hats in a posture of greeting. There are also pictures of dozens
of people, as well as flower patterns. On the ceiling there are
frescoes of clouds, the sun and the moon.
</P>
<P>
The maids look exactly the way they are depicted in terra-cotta
images unearthed in the central part of China.
</P>
<P>
Objects discovered in the tomb include a tower-shaped jar, a
porcelain bowl, a silver hair clasp and a bronze coin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
