<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Alitalia Aims to Triple Profits by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Alitalia, Italy's flag-carrying
airline, aims to triple its profits in the next three years thanks
to increased competitiveness due to privatization and its alliance
with Dutch partner KLM.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1998-2001 business plan which was published
Wednesday, the airline expects to lift profits from 202 billion
lire (about 112 million U.S. dollars) this year to 610 billion
lire (about 339 million U.S. dollars) in 2001 and to establish
itself as a player on the world markets.
</P>
<P>
Achieving these goals will depend largely on the group's
ability to negotiate the passage from a state-owned, and in part
state-financed, company to a self-supporting private enterprise.
</P>
<P>
"Privatization represents both a challenge and an opportunity
for the company which must learn to face up to the competitive
logic of financial markets," the plan said.
</P>
<P>
Alitalia, which is currently 53 percent owned by the state
holding company Iri, needs to privatize quickly. A condition of
its alliance accord with KLM was that it would make the transition
to the free market by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
As well as the partnership with KLM, Alitalia has also struck
business accords in the U.S. with Continental and Northwest in a
bid to carve out a place for itself in the global air market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
