<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aluminum Firms Mulling Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Alcoa, the largest U.S.
aluminum company, offered Wednesday to buy Reynolds Metals for 5.6
billion U.S. dollars to beef-up its number one position.
</P>
<P>
The proposed merger would create a combined revenue of 21
billion dollars. The Pittsburgh-based Alcoa had a revenue of 15.3
billion dollars in 1998 with operations in 31 countries.
</P>
<P>
The Richmond-based Reynolds Metals said its Board of Directors
will meet Sunday to work out a reply to the offer.
</P>
<P>
Alcoa's bid came hours after Alcan Aluminum of Canada said it
would buy French Pechiney AS and the aluminum and packaging untis
of Zurich-based Algroup for 9.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commodity price declines have led raw-material producers in a
number of industries to combine in a way to ensure profit by
cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
Aluminum makers are among them as prices rebound from a
five-year low in March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose
higher Wednesday as the networking company Cisco Systems
reported strong earnings and the Federal Reserve found little
evidence of rising inflation pressures in a report.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 132.65 at
10,787.80, trimming almost all losses of 138 points in the three
previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
The broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 20.50 at 1,301.93 and the technology
heavy Nasdaq index rose 74.87 at 2,564.98.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied because Cisco Systems reported Tuesday
after the trading that its net income was up 29 percent in the
fourth quarter, much better than expectations.
</P>
<P>
Investors were also encouraged to rush into the market as
the Federal Reserve survey indicates that U.S. economy is well
running on the track. The survey said widespread labor shortages
could lead to more inflationary pressures but it found only
scattered signs of mounting wage pressures and little evidence
of rising inflation pressures.
</P>
<P>
A wave of deals in the aluminum industry also helped to
push the stocks higher. Early today, Canada's Alcan Aluminum
Ltd., France's Rechinery SA and Switzerland's Alusuisse Lonza
Group announced the three combination of merger, passing
U.S.-based Alcoa as the world leader in aluminum while Alcoa
offered to buy its rival Reynolds Metal Co. for 5.6 billion U.S.
dollars in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
The market bounced back from a steep drop that has left
major indexes well below the lofty records set on July 16 after
the Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned possibility
of the second interest rates hike.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was up 6.85 at 610.22 and the
American Stock Exchange index was up 6.60 at 777.37. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies was up 5.37 at 428.19.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,865 up, 1,171 down and 526
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 782.80 million shares from 831.64
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
