<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Praises U.N. Job in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
praised the United Nations days after criticizing the world body
for its slow action in Kosovo, saying that the organization is
beginning to fulfill its key tasks there.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular briefing
that the U.N. administration is beginning to fulfill its key tasks
in Kosovo "despite formidable challenges."
</P>
<P>
"The U.N.'s goal of being present in all municipalities is also
on the way to being fulfilled," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the U.S. administration accused the U.N. of being
too slow and bureaucratic in establishing a 33,000-man
international police force.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) took advantage of a power
vacuum in the province to collect taxes, appoint local council and
carry out other governmental functions.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the changed situation now in Kosovo is reflected in
the deployment of 600 civilian police, with more on the way each
day. He said 115 U.S. police arrived in Kosovo last week, bringing
the U.S. total to 135 out of an eventual contingent of 450.
</P>
<P>
He added that the first training course for some 200 Kosovo
police candidates is scheduled to begin at the end of this
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
