<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Primary Health Care Reform in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of a loan
of 100 million U.S. dollars to support primary health care reform
in three Argentine provinces that will serve as models to extend
the reform throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The program -- to be implemented as a first step in the
provinces of Cordoba, La Pampa and Salta -- is designed to make
primary health care delivery more efficient and equitable and
introduce new health care approaches, the IDB said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
At the national level, the project will fund technical support,
information systems, and training to prepare for a new and
improved health care model that can be applied to the provinces at
their request.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the first phase of the project for the
initial three provinces is 167 million dollars. The IDB loan is
for a 20-year term, with a five-year grace period, at the variable
annual interest rate, now 6.98 percent. Local counterpart funds
total 67 million dollars. 
</P>
