<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Massive Fiscal Modernization Program for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) announced Wednesday the approval of its
largest fiscal modernization operation ever, a 2.2 billion U.S.
dollar program spanning a period of 12 years to improve fiscal
management and transparency in more than 3,800 municipalities in
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The IDB will help finance the program with three loans totaling
1.1 billion dollars, an amount that will be matched by local
counterpart funds.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase of the program, to last four years, the IDB
will provide a loan of 300 million dollars to support fiscal and
administrative modernization in 722 cities.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to increase the availability of
municipal resources for public financing, achieve greater economy
in public administration, and improve the quality and availability
of municipal services.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the program will improve transparency in municipal
management by such means as making regular information available
to the public, ensuring citizen participation in setting tax and
spending priorities, and the establishment of evaluation
procedures that take public opinion into account.
</P>
<P>
The 300-million-dollar loan is for a 20-year term, with a
four-year grace period, at the variable interest rate, now 6.98
percent. Local counterpart funds total 300 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
