<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges India, Pakistan to Observe 1991 Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday urged India and Pakistan to observe a 1991 agreement
that bans military flights close to the border without advance
notification of the other side.
</P>
<P>
"We urgently call on both sides to reinstitute this agreement
in order to avoid further loss of life and further escalation
and heightening of tensions," State Department spokesman James
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that both India and Pakistan had clearly violated
the agreement over the past few days, when an Indian plane shot
down a Pakistani reconnaissance plane close to the border and
when Pakistani planes fired on Indian fighters said to be
intruding into Pakistani airspace.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1991 agreement, Indian or Pakistani military
aircraft should not fly within 10 km of the border without
telling the other side in advance.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the 1991 agreement also provided for a prompt
investigation of any violation, by contacts between the two air
force headquarters through diplomatic channels.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States has contacted the Indian and
Pakistani governments through its embassies in those countries
and through their embassies in Washington, adding: "In those
discussions we have urged restraint and dialogue to resolve this
incident, and we will continue to meet with senior officials here
as well as in Islamabad and New Delhi."
</P>
<P>
The United States has no immediate plans to send an envoy to
the region, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
