<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Surges with Shrinking Stockpiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil prices surged to a new
22-month high on Wednesday after data showed that petroleum
stockpiles are waning.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark Brent blend crude oil settled at 20.63 U.S. dollars a
barrel in London, up 14 cents on the day, after roaring to a peak
of 20.85 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said latest weekly data from the United States showing
a decline in national inventories of crude and petroleum products
had underlined the success of OPEC (Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries) producers in tackling a glut which early this
year dragged Brent below 10 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Reuters quoted the American Petroleum Institute as saying that
U.S. crude stocks in the week to July 6 fell three million barrels
while gasoline inventories shrank by 3.5 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
U.S. crude stocks now are six percent lower than a year ago
while gasoline inventories are four percent smaller.
</P>
<P>
The latest leg of the oil rally has been spurred by the
expectation that output curbs implemented by OPEC will erase the
glut entirely in coming months.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the International Energy Agency (IEA) said in a
monthly report that OPEC compliance with the supply cuts was at 91
percent in July, compared to 87 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The Paris-based think-tank also said world oil demand was
expected to accelerate next year, while only marginal extra
supplies would emerge from non-OPEC producers.
</P>
<P>
It said a recovery in Asian economies would help double global
demand growth from 900,000 barrels a day this year to 1.8 million
bpd in 2000. It expected only 660,000 bpd of extra non-OPEC
supply.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
