<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Senate President Cleared of Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate Wednesday cleared
its President Evans Enwerem of allegations that he had a criminal
past and lied about his age while contesting for public office.
</P>
<P>
The 109-member upper house of parliament voted to accept the
report presented by three committees on ethnics, code of conduct
and public petitions, on judiciary, human rights and legal matters
and on intelligence and security.
</P>
<P>
The report of the three committees set up last week concluded
that the allegations levelled against Senate President Enwerem by
a Lagos-based magazine of Tell were baseless.
</P>
<P>
The Tell magazine alleged that the Senate president lied
variously about his age while contesting for public office and
that he was convicted for stealing while serving as a revenue
clerk in the British colonial administration before Nigeria's
independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the report by the Senate came less than a week
after Enwerem vigorously denied the allegations, dubbing it an
"orchestrated campaign to bring him down" and reduce his office.
</P>
<P>
The Senate president, who resisted pressure to step down while
investigations were being conducted, said the allegations were a
"rehash" of similar allegation made in 1992 after his election as
governor of Imo State, southeast Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
