<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Private Sector Backs Govt Bid to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian private
businessmen Wednesday voiced support for the government's
intention to pull out from the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
Arnold Kilewo, chairman of the Tanzania Private Sector
Foundation, told a press conference here that with low exports
over the years to other member states of COMESA, Tanzania has not
been benefiting in the trade arrangements within the economic
bloc.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of trade imbalances between Tanzania and the rest
of COMESA member states, there has been no meaningful equitable
partnership in trade," Kilewo said, adding that the country's
economic scale cannot compare with that of Egypt, Mauritius,
Zimbabwe and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Given Tanzania's low levels of production of industrial
products as well as low export levels, the zero tariffs proposed
to be implemented by COMESA member states in the year 2000 will
not benefit Tanzania as the country has not much to offer in terms
of trading, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kilewo said Tanzania has signed many regional and global
treaties and protocols, therefore it is time to objectively review
and assess the economic benefits of these treaties.
</P>
<P>
"When we feel that the country is not going to benefit
economically, we should not hesitate to reconsider our positions
and take remedial measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kilewo reiterated that Minister of Industries and Commerce Iddi
Simba has stated the intention of Tanzania to pull out and gave an
adequate notice of the government's intention to pull out from
COMESA as provided in relevant protocols.
</P>
<P>
On July 21, Simba announced that Tanzania plans to quit COMESA,
which surprised the organization a lot as Tanzania has always been
an active partner.
</P>
<P>
A COMESA delegation visited Tanzania early this month trying to
persuade the country not to quit the economic bloc, but Simba
insisted that Tanzania would stick to its position.
</P>
<P>
Simba stressed that it is better for Tanzania to adhere to
smaller blocs such as the 14-member Southern African Development
Community (SADC), and East African Co-operation that comprises
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian manufacturers have expressed concern that zero
tariffs would damage its local industries with the flooding of
imported goods from other COMESA members.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, set up in 1994, groups Angola, Burundi, Comoros, the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia,
Kenya, Madagascar, Malawi, Mauritius, Namibia, Rwanda, Seychelles,
Sudan, Swaziland, as well as Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
With an annual import bill of around 32 billion U.S. dollars,
COMESA forms a major market place for both internal and external
trading.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's Finance Minister Amina Salum Ali, however, has
raised concern about the union government of Tanzania to pull out
of the COMESA, saying the move runs against international trend
and indicates that Tanzania is still pursuing protectionism
policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
