<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Finds U.S. Economy Still Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Reserve said
Wednesday that the U.S. economy is still growing strongly with
widespread labor shortages reported nearly everywhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In its latest survey of economic conditions around the country,
Fed found only scattered signs of mounting wage pressures and
little evidence of rising inflation in general.
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey said, "Widespread labor shortages persist in
virtually every district, but there have been only scattered
reports of acceleration in wages." There are "some reports of
accelerating prices -- largely related to home construction -- but
there is no evidence of any broad-based pickup in consumer price
inflation," the survey added.
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey, known as the "beige book," will be used by Fed
policy-makers when they next meet on Aug. 24 to review interest
rate policies.
</P>
<P>
There has been a growing concern in financial markets that the
central bank will boost interest rates for the second time this
year because of growing fears that the economy is growing too
rapidly, given current tight labor markets.
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey did note developments that could lead to
increased inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The beige book found "continued strength in economic activity"
in late July and early August, although the book did note that
retail sales had slowed somewhat in July. It attributed a portion
of this decline to depleted inventories at retail establishments.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing, hard hit by the world currency crisis, was
showing signs of a rebound in many parts of the country, although
several districts reported continued weakness in textiles and
heavy metals such as steel.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said its Boston, Cleveland, Dallas and San Francisco
districts reported strong demand for computer and
telecommunications equipment while Cleveland and Chicago reported
orders for heavy trucks.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that housing construction was continuing at a
vigorous pace in most districts although there were signs that a
lack of available building materials and skilled workers was
limiting growth in many areas.
</P>
<P>
"Labor shortages are indicated in New York, St. Louis, Chicago,
Dallas and San Francisco -- mainly for skilled tradespeople such
as carpenters, framers and masons," the survey said. "Many
districts also report problems in obtaining key construction
materials, most notably dry wall, insulation and bricks."
</P>
<P>
The Fed survey also said that while hot and dry weather was
causing crop damage in the eastern part of the country, crops were
generally reported to be in good shape in other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990812.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
