<HEADLINE> Europe's Main Stock Markets End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets closed
broadly higher Wednesday, boosted by buoyant technology shares on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 made some modest gains following a six-month
closing low as investors took some hope from the Bank of England's
new inflation report.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index closed up 36 points, or 0.6 percent, at
6,014.4, after giving up half of its highest gain of the session.
</P>
<P>
"It's nice to see it a bit steadier," said the head of trading
at a U.S. bank. But he also said that traders remain unsettled.
And U.S. interest rate worries eroded gains in the markets as
investors balked at big moves.
</P>
<P>
Colt Telecom helped the telecommunications sector shake off
some of its recent troubles with a bullish set of second-quarter
figures. Colt shares picked up 56 pence to 1,253p.
</P>
<P>
Banks were beginning to attract interest again. LloydsTSB
shares gained 33p to 840p and HSBC shares gained 26p to 715p.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Xetra Dax closed at 5,019.69, up 18.82 from
Tuesday's close, after trading in a range of 5,010.91 to 5,017.43
in the session.
</P>
<P>
Paris share prices closed higher after merger deals lifted the
index. The CAC 40 index finished 23.60 points higher at 4,268.95.
</P>
