<HEADLINE> UNDP Tightens Financial Control, Replaces Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cambodian Government
has appointed Khem Sophoan as the new director-general for the
Cambodian Mine Action Center (CMAC) in a reaction to mismanagement
of funds allocated to CMAC by the Government, the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), which funds some 90 percent of CMAC's
action, said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new director-general was sworn in this week in the capital
Phnom Penh. In june, an audit initiated by UNDP discovered
financial irregularities in the government-allocated funds at the
mine action center.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the allegations of financial mismanagement
surfaced, we ordered an external audit of CMAC's financial
administration of these funds," Zephirin Diabre, associate
administrator of UNDP, said. "Since then, we have also initiated
an external audit of the UNDP trust fund for CMAC, even though the
use of these funds have never been questioned."
</P>
<P>
UNDP provided financial and technical assistance to CMAC since
1993. The center's budget for 1999 is 13 million U.S. dollars.
Since it was established, CMAC has cleared a total of 51.7 million
square meters of mined land, destroyed 62,000 anti-personnel
mines, 465 anti-tank mines and 178,000 items of unexploded
ordnance.
</P>
<P>
The center has trained 4,000 Cambodians in mine clearance and
educated 400,000 people in 15,000 villages in mine awareness.
Through its work, the number of people injured by landmines in
Cambodia has been reduced from 300 to 100 per month. The newly
cleared lands provide livelihoods to some 35,000 poor families.
</P>
</TEXT>
