<HEADLINE> Swissair Crash Linked to Insulation, Canadian Board Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The metalized mylar insulation
blanket was significantly linked to last September's Swissair
crash, Canadian investigators announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Transportation Safety Board of Canada, the
insulation blanket used inside the bulkheads of aircraft was a
significant factor in the spread of fire aboard doomed Swissair
Flight 111.
</P>
<P>
"There are indications that a significant source of the
combustible materials that sustained the fire was thermal
acoustical insulation blanket material," the board said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"Burnt remnants of this material, quenched by sea water, were
found in the wreckage," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Canadian media reports said the U.S. Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) is soon expected to order the
metalized mylar insulation blankets replaced on nearly 700
commercial airliners within four years.
</P>
<P>
The FAA decision, partly based on an urgent advisory from
Canadian investigators, would apply to a variety of airplanes
built by McDonnell Douglas, including the MD-80, MD-88, MD-90,
DC-10 and the MD-11, the type of plane that crashed off Nova
Scotia last September, killing all 229 aboard, the Canadian media
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
