<HEADLINE> Italy's Most Jobs Still in Old Place, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Italians are still more likely to
find work in traditional fields such as banking, medicine or the
law than in the reportedly expanding areas of services and
technology, a new report on employment showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Between 1995 and 1998 employment in banking and finance rose
13.4 percent, jobs in law soared 21.5 percent and doctors and
other medicine-related figures grew 5.2 percent, said the study by
Isfol, the Italian Institute for the Development of Professional
Training.
</P>
<P>
The report contained some other surprises. During the same
period jobs in telecommunications, an area widely believed to be
thriving, dropped by 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
"In the short and medium term most of the job possibilities
will still be in the traditional cornerstones of the economy,"
said Isfol, which is a public institution researching and
promoting professional training.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of job growth, according to the study, were
tourism, which employed 30,000 more people in 1998 than three
years earlier, and research where there were 134,000 more jobs.
</P>
<P>
The two career directions least likely to offer work to
Italians entering the job market were agriculture and any artistic
discipline, where employment fell 8.3 percent and 9.9 percent
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
